    {"id":"delta","cat":"shop","tier":"berth_top","priority":1,"badge":"2★+Green","name":"Delta","short":"Delta","lat":37.93972,"lng":23.69278,"neighborhood":"Kallithea/Faliro · SNFCC opera roof, 5th floor","tags":["€240 pp · 12-course tasting","Book ahead · €100 deposit","Arrive at sunset"],"productTags":["Only 2★ in Greece","Green Star","Ex-Maaemo chef"],"why":"The name is a fossil. This glass box rides the fifth floor of the Greek National Opera, above a Renzo Piano park laid over the silted-up Faliro delta where the Kifissos river once met the sea. Two chefs opened it in 2022 — Thanos Feskos, in from Copenhagen's Geranium, and Giorgos Papazacharias, in from Oslo's Maaemo — cooking small Greek producers through Nordic-trained technique. Feskos left in early 2025 to open his own house; Papazacharias kept the pass alone. You clear SNFCC security, ride up past the opera, and the room hands you the Saronic light before the first course lands.","address":"Syngrou Ave 364, 176 74 Kallithea","phone":"","hours":"Dinner","maps":"https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1&query=Delta+Restaurant+Athens","verdict":"The only two-MICHELIN-star kitchen in Greece — and the 2026 Athinorama jury still ranked the solo Papazacharias kitchen joint-second in the country.","signature":"Twelve-course Omnivore menu: Greek terroir driven vegetal and precise, the Saronic light on the glass.","caveat":"Not for a casual night out — a deposit-backed, full-evening gastronomic performance, not dinner.","person":"Giorgos Papazacharias, head chef — ex-Maaemo (Oslo) and creator of the 'Under' menu; co-won Greece's first two stars in 2022, then held them alone after Feskos left in 2025.","signal_chip":{"label":"2★ Green","full":"MICHELIN 2024 — two stars + Green Star, Greece's only two-star","cosign":"and we'd cross the whole city for the vegetable courses alone."},"dishes":[{"name":"Grand tasting menu","note":"Greek micro-producers driven through avant-garde technique, course after course","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Green Star vegetable courses","note":"garden vegetables cooked with protein-level respect, the plates that earned the Green Star","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Koji pepper, three tomatoes","note":"sweet pepper inoculated with koji, packed with preserved, pickled and fresh tomato, marjoram and flowers","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Cep sourdough brioche","note":"warm brioche brushed with fermented cep-mushroom honey and cep butter, the savoury bread course","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Faux sea urchin","note":"potato-and-squid-ink shell filled with bottarga, sea buckthorn and pickled rosehip","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Sweetbread sunflower","note":"sweetbread glazed with fermented cherry and saffron, crowned with a spoon of Greek caviar","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Galaktoboureko, reworked","note":"crisp sea-lettuce standing in for filo over semolina cream infused with koji and bergamot","kind":"sweet"},{"name":"Green-olive kombucha ice cream","note":"cold and briny, under pickled-pinecone jam, olive oil and Greek caviar","kind":"sweet"},{"name":"Greek-cellar wine pairing","note":"rare native Greek varieties poured glass by glass against each course","kind":"drink"}]},
    {"id":"varoulko-seaside","cat":"mainland","tier":"berth_top","priority":2,"badge":"Winch","name":"Varoulko Seaside","short":"Varoulko","lat":37.93715,"lng":23.65847,"neighborhood":"Piraeus · Mikrolimano quay, Akti Koumoundourou","tags":["EUR 50-70+ pp","Essential for the waterfront tables","Golden hour, caiques and Kastella lighting up"],"productTags":["Since 1987","1st Greek ★ 2002","16/20 in 2026"],"why":"Varoulko means 'the winch'. Lefteris Lazarou, a Piraeus ship-cook's son who cooked at sea himself, opened it in unfashionable working Piraeus in 1987 and hauled Greek fish cooking up into gastronomy — the 2002 star was Michelin's first ever awarded to Greek cuisine, anywhere. He later brought the restaurant home to the Mikrolimano quay, at eye level with the fishing caiques, and now cooks it with Giannis Yfantidis. Michelin took the star back in the 2024 selection after more than twenty years; the quay, and the fish, did not move.","address":"Akti Koumoundourou 54-56, Mikrolimano, 185 33 Piraeus","phone":"+30 210 5228400","hours":"Lunch & dinner daily","maps":"https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1&query=Varoulko+Seaside+Mikrolimano+Piraeus","verdict":"Still the single most important seafood address in Piraeus — the 2026 Greek jury rates it level with the Riviera's starred rooms.","signature":"Squid cut like tagliatelle: Lazarou's sweet, barely-set sleight, beside charcoal day-boat sea bass","caveat":"No longer a starred trophy booking, and not a cheap taverna night — come for the fish and the harbour, not the plaque.","person":"Lefteris Lazarou, chef-patron — a Piraeus ship-cook's son who cooked at sea, opened Varoulko in 1987 and won Greece's first Michelin star for Greek cuisine in 2002; now cooks with Giannis Yfantidis.","signal_chip":{"label":"16/20 '26","full":"Athinorama 2026 — Golden Hat, 16/20, level with the Riviera stars","cosign":"and we rate it Piraeus's most important fish table"},"dishes":[{"name":"Catch of the day","note":"sea bass, mullet or grouper chosen at the counter","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Octopus, charred","note":"smoke and tenderness, finished with Cretan olive oil","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Monkfish in its own broth","note":"the fish Lazarou made famous, set on mushrooms in a clear monkfish broth","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Roasted cuttlefish, caramelized lentils","note":"cuttlefish roasted soft over caramelized lentils, lifted with a bright orange sauce","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Barley with crayfish","note":"kritharoto-style barley in Lemnos wine, boukovo heat and parmesan, crayfish on top","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Taramosalata, white roe","note":"cool whipped white tarama with virgin olive oil and lemon, for the bread","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Seafood tasting menu","note":"Lazarou's monkfish, squid and day-boat fish walked across two set menus","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Assyrtiko by the glass","note":"sharp, mineral Santorini white poured cold against the harbour-fresh fish","kind":"drink"}]},
    {"id":"diporto","cat":"shop","tier":"berth_top","priority":3,"badge":"No sign","name":"Diporto","short":"Diporto","lat":37.98076,"lng":23.72576,"neighborhood":"Central Market · Sokratous & Theatrou basement","tags":["EUR 15-20 pp, cash only","No booking — ~10 tables, strangers share","Weekday lunch 12:00-15:00 with the market"],"productTags":["Since 1958","1913 lease","Cash only"],"why":"Two doors, two stairs, one cellar with no sign and no menu: a surviving 1913 lease already calls it a wine shop at 55 drachmas a month. Dimitris Koliolis — kyr-Mitsos — has worked the barrels and pots since 1958, and you eat whatever he decided at dawn, off paper-covered tables shared with market porters. The poet Kostas Varnalis drank and wrote here; clippings of his verses still yellow on the walls. In March 2024 Koliolis said the building had been sold to foreign investors with a year or two to leave; the family co-owner denied it. The pots keep going, exactly as since 1958.","address":"Sokratous 9 & Theatrou, 105 52 Athens (basement — no sign)","phone":"+30 210 3211463","hours":"Mon-Sat 08:00-19:00; Sun closed","maps":"https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1&query=Diporto+Athens","verdict":"There is no older or truer lunch in Athens: a 1913-lease wine cellar where the menu is whatever kyr-Mitsos decided at dawn.","signature":"Revithada: peppery chickpeas ladled straight from the pot, oil-slicked, bread-mopping hot","caveat":"Not for anyone needing a menu, a card machine, a clean floor plan or their own table — and maybe not here in two years.","person":"Dimitris Koliolis, 'kyr-Mitsos' — at the barrels and pots since 1958; in 2024 he told the press the building had been sold under him, and kept cooking.","signal_chip":{"label":"Heritage","full":"Athinorama 2024 — nominated for Greece's Intangible Cultural Heritage","cosign":"and we'd send you before the developers win"},"dishes":[{"name":"Fasolada","note":"the market workers' bean soup, thick enough to stand a spoon","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Gigantes","note":"giant beans baked slow in tomato and oil, soft to the fork","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Patates giachni","note":"potatoes stewed soft in tomato and oil, bread-mopping territory","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Horta","note":"wild greens boiled down soft, dressed only in olive oil and lemon","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Grilled sardines","note":"salt-crackled sardines eaten with fingers off the paper tablecloth, lemon on the side","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Barrel retsina","note":"poured from worn barrels into brass cups, resin-bright","kind":"drink"}]},
    {"id":"spondi","cat":"shop","tier":"several","priority":4,"badge":"1★","name":"Spondi","short":"Spondi","lat":37.965,"lng":23.7414,"neighborhood":"Pangrati · quiet street behind Varnava Square","tags":["€150–250 pp (est.)","Essential","Warm nights in the courtyard"],"productTags":["1★ (was 2★)","Since 1996","Bignon at the pass"],"why":"Spondi opened in 1996 and taught Athens what two Michelin stars felt like — it wore them for years before the Guide trimmed it back to one. The pass now belongs to Arnaud Bignon, a Frenchman who earned two stars of his own at London's The Greenhouse, working with head chef Manolis Demetzos. Thirty years on, the cooking is still unrepentantly French-school — classical architecture, Aegean ingredients, a whisper of Asia — and a cheese trolley is wheeled to the table, which almost no one else in this city still does. In summer it all happens in a stone courtyard under bougainvillea, behind Varnava Square where Pangrati goes quiet.","address":"Pyrronos 5, 116 36 Athens","phone":"+30 210 752 0658","hours":"From 19:30","maps":"https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1&query=Spondi+Athens","verdict":"Still the most technically exacting French kitchen in Greece — a one-star room that plates like the two-star it used to be.","signature":"Signature tasting menu: classical French architecture over Aegean ingredients, three decades of polish, an Asian inflection.","caveat":"Not for seekers of 'modern Greek' — this is unapologetically French-school fine dining, jacket-comfortable.","person":"Arnaud Bignon, executive chef — won two MICHELIN stars at London's The Greenhouse before taking Spondi's pass; runs it with head chef Manolis Demetzos.","signal_chip":{"label":"1★ MICH","full":"MICHELIN 2024 — one star (formerly two), the grande dame of Athens fine dining","cosign":"and Athinorama's 2026 jury still scores it 15.5/20 — where we'd send a purist first."},"dishes":[{"name":"Breton scallop, white truffle, Lapsang Souchong","note":"raw Breton scallop under shaved white truffle, smoked Lapsang tea perfuming the plate","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Langoustine tartare, caviar","note":"raw langoustine under Petrossian caviar, grapefruit and a cool celery coulis","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Sweetbreads, Jerusalem artichoke","note":"veal sweetbreads with artichoke, shadowed by coffee and liquorice","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Challans duck","note":"Challans duck with yellow-beetroot purée and a potato ravioli, sauce reduced dark","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Rose lamb, chickpeas","note":"lamb medallions with chickpeas, black garlic, mint and yogurt, charred spring onion alongside","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Cheese trolley","note":"a classic trolley rolled tableside — rare in Athens now","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Grand dessert","note":"the sugar-work finale, plate after plate of pastry from an obsessive kitchen","kind":"sweet"},{"name":"French-led wine pairing","note":"a deep French cellar with Greek turns, poured course by course","kind":"drink"}]},
    {"id":"soil","cat":"shop","tier":"several","priority":5,"badge":"1★ Green","name":"Soil","short":"Soil","lat":37.9662,"lng":23.741,"neighborhood":"Pangrati · Ferekydou, behind the Panathenaic Stadium","tags":["€110 pp tasting (site)","Essential · small room","Early, in the garden courtyard"],"productTags":["1★ + Green Star","Farm-to-table","Ex-Hytra chef"],"why":"Tasos Mantis came up at Hytra — the kitchen that seeded most of Athens' current starred chefs — then built the city's benchmark farm-driven room inside a restored 1925 townhouse behind the Panathenaic Stadium. Much of what lands on the plate is grown on his own plot at Alepochori, west of the city: fermented vegetables, wild herbs, Greek grains, fire kept quiet, and none of the caviar-and-lobster crutches a starred room usually leans on. In January 2026 Mantis and the Soil team opened a second act, Amphibian, at the Onassis Stegi — but this house, the one that earned the Green Star, keeps cooking.","address":"Ferekydou 5, 116 35 Athens","phone":"","hours":"Dinner","maps":"https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1&query=Soil+Restaurant+Athens","verdict":"The most convincing farm-to-table statement in Athens — a Green Star that actually tastes like one.","signature":"Seasonal tasting menu: ferments, wild herbs and heirloom vegetables treated with protein-level respect, quiet fire.","caveat":"Not for diners who measure fine dining in caviar and lobster — the garden dictates the plate.","person":"Tasos Mantis, chef-patron — the ex-Hytra chef who built Athens' defining farm-driven room; in Jan 2026 returned to the Onassis Stegi with his second act, Amphibian.","signal_chip":{"label":"1★ Green","full":"MICHELIN 2024 — one star + Green Star for sustainability","cosign":"and Athinorama's 2026 jury seconds it at 15.5/20 — the vegetable courses are why."},"dishes":[{"name":"Gambari shrimp in kombu","note":"Raw-sweet gambari shrimp sealed in a kombu-seaweed wrap under marigold and fennel, finished tableside.","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Oyster, fermented cucumber and unripe fig","note":"Cold oyster under sharp fermented cucumber and unripe fig, the brine cut clean.","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Amberjack, clams and kohlrabi","note":"Silky raw amberjack with clams and crisp kohlrabi, pickled lemon lifting the garden box beside it.","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Smoked eel, teriyaki and miso","note":"Smoked eel lacquered in teriyaki and miso, soft flesh under a charred-sweet skin.","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Beef tartare, cherry-plum and wild garlic","note":"Hand-cut beef tartare dusted with sour cherry-plum powder, horseradish heat and a ramson caper.","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Cod in kombu beurre blanc","note":"Just-set cod under a warm kombu beurre blanc with white garlic and chives.","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Goat over aspromitiko bean cream","note":"Slow-cooked goat over white aspromitiko-bean cream, spiked with a Greek XO sauce.","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Caramelised bread dessert","note":"Caramelised bread under sabayon, pumpkin-seed praline and cold buttermilk to close.","kind":"sweet"},{"name":"Seasonal tasting menu","note":"garden-led courses built on ferments, herbs and heirloom vegetables","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Vegetable-centred courses","note":"produce treated with protein-level respect — the Green Star thesis","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Greek natural-leaning pairing","note":"low-intervention Greek bottles matched to earthy plates","kind":"drink"}]},
    {"id":"ctc-urban-gastronomy","cat":"shop","tier":"several","priority":6,"badge":"1★","name":"CTC Urban Gastronomy","short":"CTC","lat":37.98,"lng":23.715,"neighborhood":"Kerameikos/Metaxourgeio · Plateon Street","tags":["€110–160 pp (est.)","Essential","Clear the evening — ~11 courses"],"productTags":["1★ Michelin","Hytra-trained","11 courses"],"why":"CTC carries the chef's initials, and the chef is Alexandros Tsiotinis, who — in Michelin's own words — 'learned on the job' at Hytra. He then drilled through France (Ferrandi, then Arpège and L'Astrance) and came home to build his own star on a hard-edged Kerameikos street, running the pass with Manolis Lekkas. The format is roughly eleven courses of Greek memory food rebuilt with French technique and a straight-faced sense of play; the bread arrives as a course in its own right, not a basket. Outside, the neighbourhood is all rail cutting and grit.","address":"Plateon 15, 104 35 Athens","phone":"","hours":"Dinner","maps":"https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1&query=CTC+Urban+Gastronomy+Athens","verdict":"The clearest single expression of the new Athenian chef generation — Hytra-raised, French-drilled, Greek at heart.","signature":"Eleven-course voyage: Greek memory dishes rebuilt with French technique and a straight-faced wit.","caveat":"Not for a quick dinner — the tasting is a three-hour, full-evening commitment.","person":"Alexandros Tsiotinis, chef-patron — apprenticed at Hytra, trained in France (Ferrandi, Arpège, L'Astrance), then built his own starred house; runs the kitchen with Manolis Lekkas.","signal_chip":{"label":"1★ MICH","full":"MICHELIN 2024 — one star, held three years running","cosign":"and Athinorama's 2026 jury scores it 15.5/20 — the bread course alone argues the case."},"dishes":[{"name":"Corn soup with lobster","note":"Silky sweet-corn soup poured over lobster at the table, warm and rich.","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Sea bass ceviche","note":"Cold citrus-cured sea bass, clean sharp acidity over near-translucent raw flesh.","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Calamari tagliatelle","note":"Calamari cut into tagliatelle ribbons, tossed with basil, pine nuts, garlic and parmesan.","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Fava 'octopus tentacle'","note":"Yellow fava shaped as an octopus tentacle, octopus demi-glace glaze, smoked eel, cherries and charred amaranth.","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Lamb and eggplant","note":"Lamb with smoked eggplant, deep and savoury — a memory dish taken apart and rebuilt.","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Rebuilt tarte tatin","note":"A deconstructed tarte tatin, warm caramelised apple against a crisp-cold counterpoint.","kind":"sweet"},{"name":"11-course tasting","note":"Greek memory dishes rebuilt with French technique and wit","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Bread service","note":"a course in itself, not an afterthought","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Greek pairing flight","note":"assyrtiko-to-xinomavro tour matched to the menu","kind":"drink"}]},
    {"id":"makris-athens","cat":"shop","tier":"several","priority":7,"badge":"1★","name":"Makris Athens","short":"Makris","lat":37.97664,"lng":23.72155,"neighborhood":"Monastiraki/Thiseio · Astiggos off lower Ermou","tags":["€130–190 pp (est.)","Essential · ask for the terrace","Golden hour, Acropolis in view"],"productTags":["1★ Michelin","Own farm","Vegan menu too"],"why":"Petros Dimas, born 1988, cooks here almost entirely from his family's organic farm at the foot of Ancient Corinth — the harvest, not the market, sets each night's menu. Below the tables, a glass floor opens onto the excavated ruins of the ancient Eleusis Inn; the neoclassical building above was, by Michelin's account, the first inn Greece ever ran for travellers. You choose between three tasting lines — Genesis, the extended Utopia, and Physis, a full vegan menu of a kind almost no starred Greek kitchen offers. Book the terrace off lower Ermou and the sacred rock sits framed in the window.","address":"Astiggos 10 & Ermou 119, 105 55 Athens","phone":"","hours":"Dinner · terrace in season","maps":"https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1&query=Makris+Athens","verdict":"Central Athens' newest Michelin star, and the only one that plates its own farm — book the terrace for the Acropolis as much as the food.","signature":"Genesis menu: own-farm produce and Greek heritage, modern technique, the Acropolis framed in the terrace glass.","caveat":"Not the address for classic-luxury, minimal-vegetable dining — the farm dictates the plate.","person":"Petros Dimas, chef-patron (b.1988) — sources most ingredients from the restaurant's own family organic farm at the foot of Ancient Corinth.","signal_chip":{"label":"1★ MICH","full":"MICHELIN Dec 2024 — one star, the newest in central Athens","cosign":"and Athinorama's 2026 jury seconds it at 15.5/20 — the terrace seals it."},"dishes":[{"name":"Aegean Luxury: oyster, champagne, caviar","note":"Cold oyster under champagne and caviar — saline, restrained luxury in a single spoonful.","kind":"dish"},{"name":"The 2 Temperatures of Greek Langoustine","note":"Greek langoustine served warm and cold at once, sweet flesh in two textures.","kind":"dish"},{"name":"White grouper, Assyrtiko and salicorn","note":"White grouper with samphire and zucchini blossom in an Assyrtiko-wine sauce, sea-clean.","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Greek mutton aged 7 days","note":"Seven-day-aged mutton with sweetbread, Evros asparagus and seasonal roots, deep and gamey.","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Cod carpaccio","note":"Thin-sliced raw cod, cold and translucent, dressed clean to let the fish speak.","kind":"dish"},{"name":"The Bouquet from My Father's Garden","note":"Thirty herbs from the family farm, raw and aromatic, presented before the meal proper.","kind":"dish"},{"name":"The Strawberry Concert","note":"Strawberries with fennel seed and pepper under basil-and-olive-oil ice cream, sweet against savoury.","kind":"sweet"},{"name":"Black Pear","note":"A dark, glossy poached-pear dessert built to look like anything but fruit.","kind":"sweet"},{"name":"Genesis tasting menu","note":"Greek heritage and farm harvest, impeccable modern technique","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Physis vegan menu","note":"a rare full-vegan tasting at starred level in Greece","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Utopia menu","note":"the extended, most ambitious expression of the kitchen","kind":"dish"}]},
    {"id":"gb-roof-garden","cat":"shop","tier":"several","priority":8,"badge":"Rooftop","name":"GB Roof Garden","short":"GB Roof Garden","lat":37.97611,"lng":23.73472,"neighborhood":"Syntagma · 8th floor, Hotel Grande Bretagne","tags":["€80–150 pp (est.)","Essential for view tables","Dusk, floodlit Acropolis ahead"],"productTags":["Acropolis view","Wine Spectator cellar","MICHELIN Plate"],"why":"The Grande Bretagne has stood on Syntagma for about 150 years, and its eighth-floor terrace gives you Parliament directly below and the floodlit Acropolis dead ahead, the bar in mid-ritual as the light goes. The kitchen runs under executive chef Asterios Koustoudis — the same hand behind the Michelin star at Tudor Hall, in the group's King George hotel next door — with Giannis Rokanas newly on the pass as chef de cuisine since early 2026. It holds a Michelin Plate, not a star, and a long-running Wine Spectator award for the cellar. Sit at the bar and you skip the dinner commitment entirely.","address":"Vasileos Georgiou A' 1, Syntagma Square, 105 64 Athens","phone":"","hours":"Breakfast to late · bar past midnight","maps":"https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1&query=GB+Roof+Garden+Athens","verdict":"The rooftop every Athens rooftop is measured against — 150 years of grand hotel below, the Acropolis full-frontal ahead.","signature":"Mediterranean plates and grand-hotel service, eight floors up, the lit Parthenon filling the whole terrace.","caveat":"You pay for the view twice — skip it if grand-hotel formality grates on you.","person":"Asterios Koustoudis, executive chef — the Michelin-awarded hand behind sister-hotel Tudor Hall's star; with chef de cuisine Giannis Rokanas, new since early 2026.","signal_chip":{"label":"MICHELIN","full":"MICHELIN — Plate, plus a long-standing Wine Spectator cellar award","cosign":"and it's still where we'd take a first-timer at dusk — the view earns it."},"dishes":[{"name":"Beef tartare, confit yolk and Metsovo cheese","note":"Hand-cut beef tartare bound with confit egg yolk, sharp Metsovo 'Rezzana' cheese shaved over.","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Charcoal-grilled octopus","note":"Charcoal-grilled octopus, tender inside, the tentacle blistered and smoky at the edges.","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Acquerello risotto with langoustines","note":"Acquerello-rice risotto, creamy and al dente, sweet langoustines folded through.","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Charcoal lamb with avgolemono foam","note":"Charcoal lamb with winter roots under a lemony avgolemono foam — char meets citrus.","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Turbot with champagne sauce","note":"Firm white turbot in a silken champagne sauce, buttery and bright.","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Lasagna with spiced rooster","note":"Lasagna layered with spiced rooster and a sharp Arseniko-Naxou cheese cream.","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Buffalo burrata","note":"Cool buffalo-milk burrata splitting to cream over seasonal garden accompaniments.","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Tiramisu","note":"Cold and cocoa-dusted, espresso-soaked layers under whipped mascarpone, the kitchen's pastry finish.","kind":"sweet"},{"name":"Mediterranean tasting or à la carte fish","note":"organic local produce under palace-kitchen discipline","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Acropolis-view cocktail","note":"bar-side ritual with the best terrace panorama in Athens","kind":"drink"},{"name":"Wine Spectator cellar pick","note":"sommelier-led dive into an awarded Greek-international cellar","kind":"drink"}]},
    {"id":"vezene","cat":"shop","tier":"several","priority":9,"badge":"Wood fire","name":"Vezené","short":"Vezené","lat":37.9765,"lng":23.7508,"neighborhood":"Ilisia · Vrasida, behind the Hilton","tags":["€60–100 pp (est.)","Essential · chef-city fixture","Late, when the fire hits cruising speed"],"productTags":["Wood-fire","Dry-aged beef","Star Wine List"],"why":"Aris Vezenes has run this room behind the Hilton since 2011, and he sources like a man with a grudge — the dry-aged beef off his wood fire is what every other Athens grill quietly copies. It is a bistro, not a tasting-menu house: whole Aegean fish laid over the same fire and treated with steakhouse seriousness, a cellar serious enough for Star Wine List recognition, and a house dessert, 'Ari's Deal Closer', with its own small cult. The room runs on swagger rather than ceremony, which is exactly why the city's own chefs book it on the night they cook for no one.","address":"Vrasida 11, 115 28 Athens","phone":"+30 210 723 2002","hours":"Dinner · Sun from 13:30","maps":"https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1&query=Vezene+Athens","verdict":"The chefs' choice for a night off — Athens' best wood-fire cooking, no tasting-menu ceremony attached.","signature":"Dry-aged steak off the wood fire, then 'Ari's Deal Closer' — swagger, not ceremony.","caveat":"Not budget, and not vegetarian-friendly at heart — this is a fire-and-meat room.","person":"Aris Vezenes, chef-owner since 2011 — an obsessive sourcer who built Athens' definitive wood-fire bistro.","signal_chip":{"label":"MICHELIN","full":"MICHELIN Guide listed + a Star Wine List cellar + a 2026 Greek Cuisine Award","cosign":"and it's the one grill we'd send another chef to — the fire does the talking."},"dishes":[{"name":"Dry-aged steak from the fire","note":"thick dry-aged beef seared over wood, deep black crust, red and resting-warm within","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Whole fish, wood-grilled","note":"whole Aegean fish laid over embers, skin blistered, flesh pulling clean off the bone","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Beef tartare pastitsio","note":"hand-cut raw beef built into a cold pastitsio, bechamel and pasta tubes turned to tartare","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Beef cheeks with kritharaki","note":"beef cheeks braised to collapse, folded through orzo slick with their own dark reduction","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Dry-aged lamb and goat over coals","note":"off-cuts dry-aged then charred over glowing coals, gamey under a hard black crust","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Portokalopita","note":"warm shredded phyllo soaked in orange syrup, edges still crackling","kind":"sweet"},{"name":"Ari's Deal Closer","note":"the house dessert with its own quiet following, sent out to end the night","kind":"sweet"},{"name":"Serious-list wine","note":"a Star Wine List cellar, poured deep in Greek bottles and beyond","kind":"drink"}]},
    {"id":"sushimou","cat":"shop","tier":"several","priority":10,"badge":"Omakase","name":"Sushimou","short":"Sushimou","lat":37.9735,"lng":23.7317,"neighborhood":"Syntagma · Skoufou, a 12-stool counter","tags":["~€55+ pp omakase (est.)","Essential · 12 stools","First sitting, counter seat"],"productTags":["12-stool omakase","Aegean edomae","Tokyo-trained"],"why":"Antonis Drakoularakos learned Japanese before he learned to cut fish this way — then decamped to Tokyo to train, and came back to run a twelve-stool counter on Skoufou where the Aegean's catch is sliced edomae-style, the old Tokyo method. There is no menu: you take a stool, the chef reads the day's fish, and the sequence is his to decide. It seats twelve and runs a few evening sittings, so it books out fast; the room is quiet and close, built for watching a knife work rather than talking across a table.","address":"Skoufou 6, 105 57 Athens","phone":"","hours":"Evening sittings","maps":"https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1&query=Sushimou+Athens","verdict":"The best sushi in Athens is Greek fish in Japanese hands — and the 2026 Golden Hats audience voted it so.","signature":"Omakase of Aegean fish cut edomae-style — twelve stools, one Tokyo-trained Greek, no menu.","caveat":"No menu, no groups, no lingering — omakase rules apply, and twelve seats fill fast.","person":"Antonis Drakoularakos, chef — mastered Japanese, trained in Tokyo, and returned to cut Aegean fish edomae-style behind his own twelve-stool counter.","signal_chip":{"label":"Audience","full":"Athinorama Golden Hats 2026 — Audience Award (the diners' vote)","cosign":"and we'd take the first stool here over any starred sushi in the city."},"dishes":[{"name":"Omakase sitting","note":"the day's Aegean catch in the chef's order, no menu, no substitutions","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Bonito nigiri","note":"lightly seared bonito over body-warm rice, a single brush of soy","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Red mullet nigiri","note":"Aegean red mullet sliced thin on vinegared rice, edomae-cured","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Crayfish nigiri","note":"sweet raw crayfish tail laid on warm shari, cool against the rice","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Sashimi of the day","note":"the morning's fish cut clean and cold, nothing on it to hide behind","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Soup course","note":"a hot broth slipped between the raw plates to reset the palate","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Build-your-own maki","note":"the last course you roll yourself, nori and rice handed across the counter","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Sake pairing","note":"a short, sharp sake list matched to Greek fish","kind":"drink"},{"name":"Local-fish nigiri","note":"Mediterranean species treated with edomae discipline","kind":"dish"}]},
    {"id":"seychelles","cat":"shop","tier":"plenty","priority":11,"badge":"Taverna","name":"Seychelles","short":"Seychelles","lat":37.98226,"lng":23.72029,"neighborhood":"Metaxourgeio · Kerameikou & Akadimou corner","tags":["EUR 30–45 pp","Phone; corner tables first-come","Early afternoon or quiet evening"],"productTags":["Since 2013","Chef's pick","Small producers"],"why":"The corner was 'Bahamas' when it first opened in December 2013; after a pause it returned in 2023 as Seychelles — original founder Fotis Foteinoglou back at the door with Kleomenis Zournatzis and Giannis Markadakis, who now runs the pass. The brief they set themselves was narrow: hold the working-class register, source from small producers across Greece, change nothing that mattered. Athinorama scored the room 14/20 in June 2024. The pavement tables on Kerameikou face a still-quiet Metaxourgeio square; inside it stays paper-tablecloth plain. It is the taverna Athens chefs name first to a colleague passing through — which is precisely why it opens this section.","address":"Kerameikou 49 & Akadimou, Metaxourgeio, 104 36 Athens","phone":"+30 211 183 4789","hours":"From 13:30","maps":"https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1&query=Seychelles+Metaxourgeio+Athens","verdict":"The starred chef of CTC names this his no-frills Greek benchmark, and the small-producer cooking holds up to the endorsement.","signature":"Pappardelle with crab sauce: wide ribbons under sweet crab, the house's one non-negotiable order.","caveat":"Not a dressed-up night out, and nothing 'exotic' despite the name — paper tablecloths, Greek register only.","person":"Fotis Foteinoglou — an original 2013 founder, back with Kleomenis Zournatzis and Giannis Markadakis, who now leads the kitchen.","signal_chip":{"label":"Chef pick","full":"THIS IS ATHENS 2026 — CTC's Alexandros Tsiotinis names it his no-frills Greek","cosign":"and the small-producer plates hold up to the name he lends it."},"dishes":[{"name":"Pappardelle with crab sauce","note":"wide ribbons under sweet crab, the one order the house will not drop","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Pappardelle with kavourmas","note":"wide ribbons under shredded buffalo kavourmas from Kerkini, cured fat melting through","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Saganaki with crab","note":"fried cheese carrying the crab thread again, crisp outside, crab picked over the top","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Beef liver with mustard & pickles","note":"blushing liver cut by sharp mustard and house pickle","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Chickpeas with feta and mint","note":"warm chickpeas under crumbled feta and torn mint, slicked with olive oil","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Cretan apaki","note":"vine-smoked Cretan pork sliced thin, cold and faintly sweet with smoke","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Greek cheese board","note":"small-producer cheeses from across Greece, salt-sharp through to buttery manouri","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Tomato salad","note":"peak-season tomatoes torn over serious olive oil and sea salt, little else","kind":"dish"}]},
    {"id":"mavros-gatos","cat":"shop","tier":"plenty","priority":12,"badge":"Grill","name":"Mavros Gatos","short":"Mavros Gatos","lat":37.9715,"lng":23.74469,"neighborhood":"Pangrati · Polemonos half-basement, near Proskopon","tags":["EUR 15–20 pp (no wine)","Phone; walk-ins off-peak","Long weekend lunch downstairs"],"productTags":["Paidakia","Chef's pick","Basement institution"],"why":"A few steps down from Polemonos, in a half-basement near Proskopon Square, the checked tablecloths and formica have not moved in decades. The order writes itself: paidakia off the charcoal, a coarse leek sausage, lamb's liver flashed with lemon, cold retsina to cut the fat. LiFO counts the lamb chops among the finest in Athens. Chef Manolis Papoutsakis, of Pharaoh, calls ribs-and-retsina here 'an Athenian staple' — the kind of sentence a working chef only spends on a room he actually returns to. Around EUR 15–20 a head without wine; the smoke gets into your jacket, and that is the point.","address":"Polemonos 4, Pangrati, 116 35 Athens","phone":"+30 210 723 6903","hours":"13:00–24:00","maps":"https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1&query=Mavros+Gatos+Pangrati+Athens","verdict":"Two of Athens' sharpest palates — Papoutsakis and LiFO — send you here for lamb chops, and the basement delivers on both counts.","signature":"Paidakia: char-crusted thin lamb chops, eaten by hand with cold resinous retsina.","caveat":"Not for terrace romantics or the offal-shy — meat, charcoal smoke and old-taverna formica, nothing softened.","signal_chip":{"label":"Chef pick","full":"THIS IS ATHENS 2026 — Pharaoh's Manolis Papoutsakis calls lamb-and-retsina here 'an Athenian staple'","cosign":"and LiFO ranks the paidakia among the city's best."},"dishes":[{"name":"Paidakia (lamb chops)","note":"thin lamb chops char-crusted over coals, eaten by hand, fat crackling at the edge","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Homemade leek sausage","note":"coarse house sausage, leek-sweet, blistered off the grill","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Grilled liver","note":"lamb's liver flashed over the fire, lemon-sharpened, still pink through","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Lahanodolmades","note":"cabbage rolls of rice and mince under a lemony avgolemono blanket","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Saganaki","note":"fried cheese with a crisp thin crust and a soft creamy middle","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Fava","note":"yellow split-pea puree under raw onion and a thread of olive oil","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Kolokithokeftedes","note":"courgette fritters, crisp-edged and flecked with herbs, hot from the pan","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Retsina","note":"cold resinous house pour, poured to cut the grill fat","kind":"drink"}]},
    {"id":"psarokastella","cat":"mainland","tier":"plenty","priority":13,"badge":"Fish","name":"Psarokastella","short":"Psarokastella","lat":37.94262,"lng":23.65549,"neighborhood":"Kastella, Piraeus · Skra lane above Mikrolimano","tags":["Fish by weight, day-boat","Phone ahead — tiny room","Warm evening after the climb"],"productTags":["Since 1986","Day-boat fish","MasterChef family"],"why":"In 1986 a Cretan fish merchant began grilling sardines on the veranda of the family house, up a plain lane on the Kastella slope above Mikrolimano. His daughter Maria Loukaki runs it now with her husband Kostas Nestoras; their son Nestoras won MasterChef Greece in 2025 and calls the four-square-metre kitchen his second home. Two Aegean lines meet on the plate — the father's Cretan fish trade, the mother's Smyrniot family that resettled on Chios. Maria Ntioudi of Merceri keeps it as her secret, praising a kitchen that chooses its seafood fresh every day. No view, no menu theatre — you climb for the fish.","address":"Skra 19, Kastella, 185 47 Piraeus","phone":"+30 210 422 2237","hours":"Call ahead","maps":"https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1&query=Psarokastella+Kastella+Piraeus","verdict":"The Merceri chefs vouch that this family buys its fish daily — and every grilled plate off the Kastella veranda proves the habit.","signature":"Day-boat fish, grilled: chosen that morning, dressed only in olive oil and lemon.","caveat":"Not a Mikrolimano quay show — no sea view, no theatre; you walk up a residential lane purely to eat.","person":"Maria Loukaki and her husband Kostas Nestoras — parents of MasterChef Greece 2025 winner Nestoras Nestoras; started in 1986 by Maria's father, a Cretan fish merchant.","signal_chip":{"label":"Chef pick","full":"THIS IS ATHENS 2026 — Merceri's Maria Ntioudi keeps it as her secret eaterie","cosign":"and the day-boat fish proves her right."},"dishes":[{"name":"Day-boat fish, grilled","note":"chosen that morning off the ice, dressed only in olive oil and lemon, char lines from the coals","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Taramosalata with bottarga","note":"silky pale roe spread whipped smooth, a salty crown of Messolonghi bottarga on top","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Garlic shrimp saganaki","note":"shrimp bubbling in a small pan of garlic, tomato and oil, hot enough to spit","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Squid with capers","note":"tender squid rings, briny caper bite, olive oil and a squeeze of lemon","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Sardeles sti schara (grilled sardines)","note":"the founding plate — oily, char-blistered, sea-salted, eaten hot off the veranda coals with lemon","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Chtapodi krasato (octopus in wine)","note":"octopus stained deep red, tender under a sweet wine-and-vinegar reduction, oregano on top","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Marides tiganites (fried small fish)","note":"flour-dusted picarel fried crisp and whole, eaten head-and-all, salt and a lemon squeeze","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Fava","note":"warm yellow split-pea puree pooled with olive oil, raw onion and capers scattered over","kind":"dish"}]},
    {"id":"steki-tou-ilia","cat":"shop","tier":"plenty","priority":14,"badge":"Paidakia","name":"To Steki tou Ilia","short":"Steki tou Ilia","lat":37.97693,"lng":23.71591,"neighborhood":"Thissio · rail-side lane, Ano Petralona border","tags":["EUR 20–30 pp","Phone; weekend queues","Saturday lunch under the trees"],"productTags":["Since 1981","Chef's pick","Paidakia"],"why":"Ilias Kolovis lit the grill on this pedestrian lane beside the electric railway in 1981; by 1992 the paidakia queue had outgrown one room, so he opened a second a few metres along the same strip. His children keep both. The menu is a short grill list and nothing more — lamb chops by the kilo, lemony liver, hand-rolled meatballs, rough-cut potatoes, bitter greens — eaten in courtyards under olive, mulberry and medlar. Andreas Kiltsiksis of Feyrouz sends you here for 'some of the tastiest lamb chops', ISAP trains rattling past the tables. Around EUR 20–30 a head; closed Monday, when it is nothing at all.","address":"Thessalonikis 7, Thissio, 118 51 Athens (2nd house: Eptachalkou 5)","phone":"+30 210 342 2407","hours":"Dinner; Sat–Sun lunch; Mon closed","maps":"https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1&query=To+Steki+tou+Ilia+Thissio+Athens","verdict":"A 1981 grill that has never needed a second idea — Feyrouz's chef and every Saturday queue agree no one grills a better lamb chop in Athens.","signature":"Paidakia: thin lamb chops char-edged off the coals, eaten with fingers under mulberry shade.","caveat":"Vegetarians and slow-wine-dinner people have no business here — a grill with tables, and Monday it is shut.","person":"Ilias Kolovis — lit the grill in 1981 and added the second room in 1992 as the paidakia queue outgrew the first; his children now run both houses.","signal_chip":{"label":"Chef pick","full":"THIS IS ATHENS 2026 — Feyrouz's Andreas Kiltsiksis sends you for 'the tastiest lamb chops'","cosign":"and 1981 never needed a second idea to earn it."},"dishes":[{"name":"Paidakia","note":"thin lamb chops, char-edged off the coals, salt and oregano, eaten with fingers under mulberry shade","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Lemonati sikotaria","note":"lamb liver and offal, seared quick, finished under a hot lemon-and-oregano sheen","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Keftedakia","note":"juicy hand-rolled meatballs, oregano-scented, crust from the grill, soft inside","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Horta","note":"bitter boiled greens, warm, lemon-drenched and glossed with oil — the chops' answer","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Bifteki","note":"thick charcoal-grilled minced patty, smoky crust, juices running, raw onion and oregano","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Kontosouvli","note":"fatty pork turned slow on the spit, crackling edges, cut in warm smoky chunks","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Patates tiganites","note":"hand-cut potatoes fried crisp and salted, dusted with oregano — the chops' partner","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Loukaniko","note":"coarse village pork sausage, casing blistered on the grill, fennel and orange-peel warmth","kind":"dish"}]},
    {"id":"feyrouz","cat":"shop","tier":"plenty","priority":15,"badge":"Levantine","name":"Feyrouz","short":"Feyrouz","lat":37.97815,"lng":23.72774,"neighborhood":"Psyrri · Karori & Agathonos corner","tags":["~EUR 5–10 pp","None — counter and stools","Lunch, lahmajun leaving the oven"],"productTags":["Since 2014","Antiochian","Lahmajun"],"why":"The Dandachi family carried Antioch with them — Antakya to Istanbul to a Psyrri corner in 2014 — and named the counter for the mother at the oven, Feyrouz, herself named for the great Arab singer. Her sons Andreas and Savvas roll lahmajun on Karori lane: paper-thin dough, a minced-beef spice paste, sumac and lemon, five euros or so. Athens, a city rebuilt by Anatolian refugees a century ago, recognised the story on sight — the lunchtime queue is 1922 retold in dough. Peinirli boats, winter lentil soup and pistachio sweets from the family patisserie fill out a counter that ends when the dough does.","address":"Karori 23 & Agathonos 1, 105 51 Athens","phone":"","hours":"Lunch into evening","maps":"https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1&query=Feyrouz+Psyrri+Athens","verdict":"The best few-euro flatbread in central Athens — and a chef who skips it because 'it isn't Greek' has misread what Athens street food became.","signature":"Lahmajun, rolled hot: thin blistered dough, spiced beef, greens, sumac-and-lemon sharpness.","caveat":"Not the stop for souvlaki or a lingering table — Levantine counter food with a few stools, and it sells out.","person":"Named for the family's matriarch and cook Feyrouz (Eleni), born in Antioch; the Dandachi route ran Antakya–Istanbul–Athens, and sons Andreas and Savvas run the counter (opened 2014).","dishes":[{"name":"Lahmajun, rolled","note":"paper-thin dough roasted with minced-beef spice paste, rolled hot with babaganoush, salad and pomegranate molasses","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Peinirli boat","note":"open butter-crumbed dough boat, molten cheese heart, warm from the oven","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Lahmanikon (vegetarian)","note":"whole-grain dough roasted with eight vegetables and herbs, rolled with tabbouleh and hummus bi tahina","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Za'atar lahmatzun","note":"hand-kneaded sourdough roasted with za'atar wild thyme and dried nuts, herb-scented and warm","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Sujuk peinirli","note":"dough boat baked over spiced Armenian beef sausage, kasseri and edam melting into tomato","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Mahluta (red-lentil soup)","note":"hot red-lentil soup with fennel and pumpkin, homemade chicken broth, freshly ground carum","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Kunefe","note":"shredded kadaif crisped over melting Cretan myzithra, drenched hot in heather-honey syrup","kind":"sweet"},{"name":"Baklava with Aegina pistachios","note":"thin yufka layered with roasted pistachios and citrus, bound in clarified butter","kind":"sweet"},{"name":"Vegan lahmajun / greens","note":"the vegetarian order that converts carnivores","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Pistachio sweets","note":"buttery Anatolian aromatics from the family patisserie","kind":"sweet"}]},
    {"id":"nolan","cat":"shop","tier":"plenty","priority":16,"badge":"Bib","name":"Nolan","short":"Nolan","lat":37.9744,"lng":23.7323,"neighborhood":"Syntagma · Voulis St, steps from the square","tags":["EUR 25–45 pp","Recommended","Early dinner before the crush"],"productTags":["Bib Gourmand","Greek-Asian","Two sittings"],"why":"Founding chef Sotiris Kontizas — a MasterChef Greece judge — left in September 2024, and the small Voulis room reopened that December as 'Nolan 2.0' under Michalis Nourloglou. The thesis held: Greek raw materials pulled through Japanese, Vietnamese, Korean and Chinese technique, fast and warm across two tight sittings. Sea-bream tartare, breaded beef cheeks with truffle, a rotating blackboard plate — small plates built to move. The Bib Gourmand it earned in the 2024 Michelin selection carried into 2026 through the handover. It taught Athens that comfort food could speak two languages at once; the second act keeps that argument alive on a Syntagma side street.","address":"Voulis 31-33, 105 57 Athens","phone":"","hours":"Lunch & dinner (Mon–Sat)","maps":"https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1&query=Nolan+Voulis+Athens","verdict":"Nolan's second act still earns its Bib: a Syntagma room where Greek produce speaks fluent Japanese, Vietnamese, Korean and Chinese.","signature":"Sea-bream tartare: Greek raw fish under Asian seasoning, one of the room's current signatures.","caveat":"Not a lingering-table restaurant — turnover across two sittings is part of the deal.","person":"Michalis Nourloglou, executive chef since Dec 2024 — steers 'Nolan 2.0', a Greek-meets-Asian bistro; founding chef Sotiris Kontizas departed in Sept 2024.","signal_chip":{"label":"Bib","full":"MICHELIN 2024 — Bib Gourmand, carried into the 2026 selection","cosign":"and Nourloglou's second act keeps it honestly."},"dishes":[{"name":"Sea-bream tartare","note":"Greek raw fish diced cool, dried fruit and a hint of citrus lifting the seasoning","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Breaded beef cheeks with truffle","note":"slow-cooked cheeks shredded and breaded, crisp crumb, on cream under shaved truffle","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Soba noodles, smoked salmon and tahini","note":"cold buckwheat soba coated in sesame tahini, chunks of smoked salmon, scallion and sesame","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Mediterranean tuna with ponzu","note":"cool raw tuna slices under sharp citrus-soy ponzu, clean, a sesame edge","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Steamed bao bun","note":"soft pillowy steamed bun folded around a braised filling, warm, faintly sweet dough","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Courgette with miso and smoked pork cheek","note":"grilled courgette lacquered in sweet miso, smoked pork cheek adding a deep umami back-note","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Sirloin with charred leeks","note":"seared sirloin in a teriyaki-dark glaze beside smoke-blackened leeks","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Rotating Greek-Asian plate","note":"the blackboard dish from Nourloglou's pass, built small to move across the two sittings","kind":"dish"}]},
    {"id":"marili","cat":"shop","tier":"plenty","priority":17,"badge":"Georgian","name":"Marili","short":"Marili","lat":38.0025,"lng":23.73745,"neighborhood":"Kypseli · Agias Zonis pedestrian lane off Fokionos Negri","tags":["~EUR 4–9 pp","None — takeaway counter","Mid-morning, khachapuri molten"],"productTags":["Since 2023","Georgian tone oven","Khachapuri"],"why":"Natia Nadareishvili named her oven Marili — 'salt' in Georgian — for the one thing a baker back home is never forgiven for getting wrong. In 2023 she and Londa Glonti set a tone, the bell-mouthed clay oven, in a shopfront window on Agias Zonis, the pedestrian lane off Fokionos Negri where Kypseli still shops on foot. Khachapuri comes off the stone molten and takes butter; beside it sit lavash and pinched pouches — potato and pepper, bean and onion, mushroom and herb — the tell of a cook working from memory. In a quarter that once took in Anatolian Greeks and now holds Georgians, West Africans and Filipinos, this is the Caucasus corner of the newest map.","address":"Agias Zonis 26, 113 61 Kypseli, Athens","phone":"+30 211 425 2269","hours":"Daytime; call ahead","maps":"https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1&query=Marili+Georgian+bakery+Kypseli+Athens","verdict":"Athens' Georgian corner: a real tone-oven bakery where the khachapuri leaves the stone molten — the Caucasus answer to what here is special and not Greek.","signature":"Khachapuri imeruli: molten fresh cow's-milk cheese in blistered dough, buttered straight from the clay tone.","caveat":"Not a lingering table or a full dinner — a tiny bake-shop counter; ring ahead before a special trip up.","person":"Natia Nadareishvili — born and raised in Georgia, opened Marili in 2023 with Londa Glonti; named it for the Georgian word for salt.","dishes":[{"name":"Lobiani (bean-filled)","note":"Warm flatbread packed with spiced mashed beans and onion, dense and faintly smoky off the clay wall.","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Potato & pepper pouch","note":"Pinched dough pocket around soft potato and sweet pepper, steam rising when you tear it open.","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Mushroom & herb pouch","note":"Earthy sauteed mushroom and green herbs sealed inside blistered dough, hot from the tone.","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Lavash","note":"Long flatbread pulled off the clay wall, blistered and chewy, torn warm to wrap the cheese.","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Khachapuri (imeruli)","note":"molten cow's-milk cheese in blistered dough, buttered from the tone","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Filled dough pouches","note":"pinched pockets — potato & pepper, bean & onion, mushroom","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Lavash & Georgian pites","note":"flatbread and daily pies baked in the clay tone","kind":"dish"}]},
    {"id":"akra","cat":"shop","tier":"plenty","priority":18,"badge":"Live-fire","name":"Akra","short":"Akra","lat":37.9683,"lng":23.7456,"neighborhood":"Pangrati · Amynta St, near Proskopon Square","tags":["EUR 30–55 pp","Recommended","Late dinner, fire in full swing"],"productTags":["Bib Gourmand","Live-fire","Since 2023"],"why":"Akra opened in 2023 near Proskopon Square and quickly became the room new Pangrati orbits. A charcoal fire burns continuously; Giannis Loukakis, out of Mourga, cooks whatever the market gave that morning over it, and the menu is rewritten daily around it. The signature at the door is not a grill but a bakery — Spyros Pediaditakis runs an in-house pastry and cake counter you pass on the way in. Michelin made it a Bib Gourmand in the 2024 Greece selection. Loud, convivial, half-portions on offer; walk-ins wait at peak. It reads as a neighbourhood joint and cooks like a serious kitchen.","address":"Amynta 12, 116 35 Athens","phone":"+30 210 725 1116","hours":"All-day into dinner","maps":"https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1&query=Akra+Pangrati+Athens","verdict":"The Bib that defines new Pangrati — a daily-changing live-fire kitchen with a working bakery at its own front door.","signature":"Daily fire-cooked market dish: the morning's best haul, seared over the continuously burning charcoal.","caveat":"Not for vegetarians or quiet-dinner seekers — it is loud, meat-forward and fire-led.","person":"Giannis Loukakis (ex-Mourga) leads the live-fire kitchen; Spyros Pediaditakis runs the in-house bakery and pastry at the entrance.","signal_chip":{"label":"Bib","full":"MICHELIN 2024 — Bib Gourmand, a new entry held into 2026","cosign":"and new Pangrati now orbits its open fire."},"dishes":[{"name":"Charred wild greens (horta)","note":"Market greens blackened at the edges over charcoal, dressed hot with lemon and olive oil.","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Fire-grilled fish of the day","note":"Whole from the morning market, skin blistered and salt-crackled over the live coals.","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Charcoal-grilled lamb or pork","note":"The day's cut seared on the continuous fire, charred crust giving to a pink centre.","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Grilled artichokes","note":"Trimmed hearts caught over the flame, smoky and tender, a squeeze of lemon.","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Pea puree with Syros sour cheese","note":"Cool green puree under sharp island cheese, warm bread to wipe the plate.","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Caramelised tart","note":"Burnt-sugar top cracking over soft custard, from the bakery you passed coming in.","kind":"sweet"},{"name":"Fresh-milk ice cream with chocolate mousse","note":"Cold local-milk ice cream beside a dark handmade mousse, both from the front counter.","kind":"sweet"},{"name":"Daily fire-cooked market dish","note":"whatever the market gave, over the continuous charcoal fire","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Wood-fired vegetables","note":"char and smoke over live fire","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Bakery pastry from the door","note":"from Pediaditakis's in-house bakery at the entrance","kind":"dish"}]},
    {"id":"pharaoh","cat":"shop","tier":"plenty","priority":19,"badge":"Wood-oven","name":"Pharaoh","short":"Pharaoh","lat":37.9872,"lng":23.729,"neighborhood":"Exarcheia edge · Solomou St","tags":["EUR 30–55 pp","Recommended (e-table)","When the blackboard changes — nightly"],"productTags":["Bib Gourmand","Wood oven, no gas","400+ natural wines"],"why":"Manolis Papoutsakis — the Cretan chef behind Thessaloniki's Charoupi — cooks on Solomou with no electricity or gas in the kitchen at all: wood stoves, charcoal, a wood-fired oven, and a blackboard rewritten almost nightly around the market. Restaurant, bar and wine shop share one room, and the list runs natural-wine-first, more than four hundred labels along the wall. Michelin named it a Bib Gourmand in the 2024 Greece selection, alongside Akra. Regional Greek recipes — island and mountain — come back respectfully updated, lamb and pulses and greens, whatever the day decided. The wine you drink you can carry out the door.","address":"Solomou 54, 106 82 Athens","phone":"+30 210 380 8412","hours":"Dinner","maps":"https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1&query=Pharaoh+Solomou+Athens","verdict":"Athens' best argument that tradition, a wood oven and natural wine make a modern restaurant — and we would cross town for the blackboard.","signature":"Wood-oven daily roast: an island or mountain recipe the blackboard picked that morning, slow-cooked in a kitchen with no gas.","caveat":"Menu control-freaks beware — you eat what the day decided, not what you planned.","person":"Manolis Papoutsakis, chef — revisits Greek regional tradition with a contemporary hand and a daily-changing menu, in a kitchen that runs on no electricity or gas.","signal_chip":{"label":"Bib","full":"MICHELIN 2024 — Bib Gourmand, held into the 2026 selection","cosign":"and we'd cross town for the wood oven alone."},"dishes":[{"name":"Taramosalata with bottarga","note":"Whipped grey-mullet roe smoothed onto sourdough, shaved bottarga and wild greens laid over the top.","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Dolmadakia","note":"Vine leaves rolled tight around rice and herbs, soft enough to fall apart, lemon over.","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Slow-cooked lamb with hilopites","note":"Wood-oven lamb pulled apart over hand-cut egg-pasta squares soaking up the pan juices.","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Chestnut stew","note":"Chestnuts simmered slow and low on the wood stove, earthy and faintly sweet.","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Wild greens (horta)","note":"Bitter market greens boiled soft, warm under olive oil and a hard squeeze of lemon.","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Galaktoboureko","note":"Warm semolina custard wrapped in crackling filo, syrup poured over at the table.","kind":"sweet"},{"name":"Wood-oven daily roast","note":"whatever the market gave, slow-cooked in the wood oven","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Regional Greek classic of the day","note":"island or mountain recipe, respectfully updated","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Natural wine from the shop wall","note":"restaurant, bar and wine shop in one — drink accordingly","kind":"drink"}]},
    {"id":"skalakia","cat":"shop","tier":"plenty","priority":20,"badge":"Grill","name":"Skalakia","short":"Skalakia","lat":37.97703,"lng":23.75659,"neighborhood":"Ilisia · Dionysiou Aiginitou, hospital district","tags":["EUR 20–25 pp","Phone — small room","Sunday lunch, or spring wisteria"],"productTags":["Since 1967","Chef's secret gem","Sweetbreads"],"why":"Skalakia has fed the same Ilisia block since 1967, a few steps up from a quiet residential corner in the hospital district, pavement tables under wisteria in spring. It fed politicians, hospital doctors and journalists then and changed nothing since — which is the whole aesthetic. The grill runs to offal and old-guard plates: lamb sweetbreads crisp-edged and custard-soft, liver glossed in hot lemon, meatballs, silky fava, a house tsipouro to open. Manolis Papoutsakis of Pharaoh lets slip that it is his 'secret gem' for the best grilled sweetbreads and liver. Weekdays it opens at 16:00; Sunday is lunch only, doors down by 17:00.","address":"Dionysiou Aiginitou 32, Ilisia, 115 28 Athens","phone":"+30 210 722 9290","hours":"From 16:00; Sat 13:00; Sun lunch only","maps":"https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1&query=Skalakia+Ilisia+Athens","verdict":"A 1967 neighbourhood grill that outlived every Athens trend by changing nothing — Papoutsakis calls the sweetbreads and liver his secret gem, and he is right.","signature":"Grilled lamb sweetbreads: crisp outside, custard-soft within, lemon and a shot of tsipouro.","caveat":"Not for the offal-shy or decor-hunters — unchanged-since-1967 consistency is the look, and Sunday dinner does not exist.","signal_chip":{"label":"Chef pick","full":"THIS IS ATHENS 2026 — Pharaoh's Papoutsakis calls it his 'secret gem' for sweetbreads and liver","cosign":"and 1967 kept every reason he means."},"dishes":[{"name":"Kokoretsi","note":"Lamb offal wound on the spit and charcoal-charred, crisp outside, oregano and lemon.","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Paidakia (grilled lamb chops)","note":"Thin chops off the coals, fat crackling, dressed with salt, oregano and lemon.","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Arni sto fourno (oven lamb)","note":"Roasted slow until it slides off the bone in its own pan juices.","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Boiled vlita and baby zucchini","note":"Warm amaranth greens and small courgettes soft under olive oil and lemon.","kind":"dish"},{"name":"House tsipouro","note":"The cold pour to open the table, grassy and sharp on the tongue.","kind":"drink"},{"name":"Horiatiki (Greek salad)","note":"Cool tomato, cucumber and onion under a slab of feta, oregano and olive oil.","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Grilled lamb sweetbreads","note":"crisp-edged glykadia, soft centre, lemon squeeze","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Lemon-braised liver","note":"sikotaria glossed in hot lemon sauce","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Keftedakia","note":"the 'excellent meatballs' of the old guard","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Fava","note":"silky split-pea puree, raw onion, olive oil","kind":"dish"}]},
    {"id":"ariston","cat":"shop","tier":"plenty","priority":21,"badge":"Pie 1910","name":"Ariston","short":"Ariston 1910","lat":37.97672,"lng":23.73265,"neighborhood":"Syntagma · Voulis 10, one block behind the square","tags":["~EUR 2–6 pp","Takeaway only","Weekday mid-morning, warm trays"],"productTags":["Since 1910","Heritage monument","Tyropita kourou"],"why":"The dough is the story. Anastasios Lombotesis carried a kourou recipe from Constantinople in 1910 and set up a few steps behind the old Parliament on Voulis; four generations later — Tatiana Lombotesi and Theodoris Panagiotopoulos among them — the same family still rolls it into more than a hundred pie styles. Deputies queued so reliably that the tyropita kourou became the unofficial breakfast of Greek politics. The Greek state declared it a Monument of Modern Cultural Heritage in 2018. There are no tables and never have been: you buy, you walk, you eat on Voulis. Closed Sunday; the warm trays empty with the morning.","address":"Voulis 10, 105 63 Athens","phone":"+30 210 322 7626","hours":"Mornings, Mon–Sat","maps":"https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1&query=Ariston+1910+Voulis+Athens","verdict":"Over a century on, the tyropita kourou here is still the one to beat — order anything else first and you have wasted a warm one.","signature":"Tyropita kourou: half-moon of thick, buttery, crumbling crust around salty molten feta, eaten warm.","caveat":"No tables, no coffee theatre — buy, walk, eat; and the trays empty with the morning.","person":"Founded 1910 by Anastasios Lombotesis, who carried the kourou recipe from Constantinople; the fourth generation — Tatiana Lombotesi and Theodoris Panagiotopoulos among them — still rolls the dough.","signal_chip":{"label":"Heritage","full":"GREEK STATE 2018 — declared a Monument of Modern Cultural Heritage","cosign":"and four generations earned the plaque."},"dishes":[{"name":"Tyropita kourou","note":"the 1910 half-moon: short, crumbling butter crust round salted feta that pulls molten when torn warm","kind":"buy"},{"name":"Spanakopita","note":"spinach and wild greens with dill, folded into the same century-old kourou dough","kind":"buy"},{"name":"Melitzanopita","note":"smoky roasted eggplant, dark and soft, sealed in a crisp-edged pastry","kind":"buy"},{"name":"Loukanikopita","note":"a whole spiced sausage baked inside phyllo, its fat crackling through the crust","kind":"buy"},{"name":"Kotopita","note":"shredded chicken in a warm, lightly creamy filling under flaking golden layers","kind":"buy"},{"name":"Kaseropita","note":"sharp yellow kasseri melting inside a crisp, faintly greasy short crust","kind":"buy"},{"name":"Bougatsa","note":"the sweet one: warm vanilla custard in phyllo, dusted with icing sugar and cinnamon","kind":"sweet"},{"name":"A dozen kourou for the boat","note":"they travel warm and reheat crisp; provision the crew mess","kind":"buy"}]},
    {"id":"koulouri-tou-psirri","cat":"shop","tier":"plenty","priority":22,"badge":"Koulouri","name":"To Koulouri tou Psirri","short":"Koulouri tou Psirri","lat":37.978,"lng":23.72455,"neighborhood":"Psyrri · Karaiskaki, off Plateia Iroon","tags":["Under EUR 2","None — bakery counter","05:00–07:00, hot at dawn"],"productTags":["Since 1965","At-source","~7,000/day"],"why":"The koulouri — the sesame ring Athens inherited from Byzantium through Thessaloniki's refugee bakers — has one beating heart in the centre, and it is this Karaiskaki workshop off Plateia Iroon. Ilias Papageorgiou, whom Greek press calls the pioneer of the koulouri, bought the bakery in 1965 (the building dates to 1934) and turned it into the plant behind almost every street-corner koulouri cart downtown — on the order of seven thousand rings a day. The whole city's koulouri economy walks out this one door before sunrise. Under two euros a ring; no seats, no coffee, no ceremony — follow the sesame smell and buy at the source.","address":"Karaiskaki 23, Psyrri, 105 54 Athens","phone":"+30 210 321 5962","hours":"Dawn onward","maps":"https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1&query=To+Koulouri+tou+Psirri+Athens","verdict":"Nearly every koulouri sold from a downtown street cart was born in this one Psyrri bakery — buy it here at 05:00 and the difference is the crunch.","signature":"A hot sesame koulouri at dawn: thin crackling ring, toasted sesame, steam in the cold.","caveat":"Not for anyone wanting a seat, a coffee or a schedule — a flour-dusted production bakery with a till.","person":"Ilias Papageorgiou — the baker Greek press calls 'the pioneer of the koulouri'; bought the 1934 bakery in 1965 and grew it into the workshop behind most of downtown's koulouri carts.","dishes":[{"name":"Classic thin sesame ring","note":"Thessaloniki-style: thin, crackling, densely sesame-crusted, best within the first hour","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Braided soft koulouri","note":"the fluffy plait, chewier and closer to a breakfast bread","kind":"dish"},{"name":"A dozen rings for the crew","note":"cheapest good provisioning in Athens, dawn pickup while they are still hot","kind":"buy"},{"name":"Classic thin koulouri","note":"Thessaloniki-style crisp ring, sesame-crusted, best within the hour","kind":"dish"}]},
    {"id":"olympion","cat":"shop","tier":"plenty","priority":23,"badge":"Mageireio","name":"Olympion","short":"Olympion","lat":37.96656,"lng":23.73454,"neighborhood":"Mets · Anapafseos, below the Panathenaic Stadium","tags":["~EUR 6–9 a plate","None — read the pots","Weekday lunch 13:00–15:00"],"productTags":["Mageireio","Window of pots","Under EUR 15"],"why":"Where Anapafseos climbs from the marble of the Panathenaic Stadium toward the cypresses of the First Cemetery, a hand-painted 'Παραδοσιακόν Καφεπωλείον' sign hangs over a window of steaming trays. This is a mageireio in the oldest Athenian sense: no printed menu, no waiter's recital — you walk to the glass case, read the day's pots, and point. Zisimos Drakontaeidis has ladled them since the early 2000s, for years cooking beside his mother. Gemista, courgettes in egg-lemon, lemony veal, oven giant beans — a cooked plate runs six to nine euros, a full lunch with wine rarely past fifteen. Athens Voice called the prices 'too good to be true'.","address":"Anapafseos 9, Mets, 116 36 Athens","phone":"+30 210 924 4388","hours":"Lunch, Mon–Sat","maps":"https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1&query=Olympion+Anapafseos+Mets+Athens","verdict":"The cheapest honest plate in the guide: read a Mets window of pots and eat the day's home cooking for less than a downtown cocktail.","signature":"Kolokithakia gemista me avgolemono: courgettes stuffed and bound in egg-lemon, the tender-green house plate.","caveat":"No dinner service, no menu, no polish — a daytime window of pots on a residential lane; come at lunch or not at all.","person":"Zisimos Drakontaeidis — the proprietor on the business registry — has ladled the daily pots here since the early 2000s, for years cooking alongside his mother in the plain old-Athens style.","dishes":[{"name":"Kolokithakia gemista me avgolemono","note":"courgettes stuffed with rice and herbs, bound in a lemony egg sauce, tender-green","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Gemista","note":"tomatoes and peppers packed with herbed rice, baked soft in their own juices","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Moschari lemonato","note":"veal simmered slow in lemon and oil until it forks apart; kokkinisto in red sauce sits beside it","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Gigantes plaki","note":"oven giant beans in tomato and dill, creamy inside, skins caramelised at the tray edge","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Lahanodolmades","note":"cabbage leaves rolled round rice and mince, warm under more of the egg-lemon","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Pastitsio","note":"layered macaroni and mince under a thick baked béchamel, cut in squares","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Keftedes","note":"pan-fried herbed meatballs, cumin and mint worked through the mince","kind":"dish"},{"name":"A tub of the day's mageirefta","note":"the pots ladle straight into takeaway tubs — cheap, honest provisioning","kind":"buy"},{"name":"Moschari lemonato / kokkinisto","note":"veal braised lemony or in red sauce — the meat pot","kind":"dish"}]},
    {"id":"stani","cat":"shop","tier":"plenty","priority":24,"badge":"Dairy bar","name":"Stani","short":"Stani","lat":37.98543,"lng":23.72793,"neighborhood":"Omonia · Marikas Kotopouli St","tags":["~EUR 5–10 pp","None — counter service","Breakfast, or the mid-afternoon lull"],"productTags":["Since 1931","Last galaktopoleio","Fair gold 1953"],"why":"Nikolaos Karageorgos, a dairyman from Fokida, opened Stani in the Evangelistria quarter of Piraeus in 1931; when wartime bombing wrecked the port the family refounded it off Omonia in 1949, where it still stands. His grandson Thanasis runs it now, still buying from the family's mountain herds and honey men. Of the roughly sixteen hundred galaktopoleia Athens and Piraeus counted at mid-century, this is the one left. Sheep's-milk yogurt under fir honey and walnuts, anthogalo that swallows a litre and a half of milk per glass, rice pudding made fresh daily. A gritty Omonia block — you come for the dairy, not the street.","address":"Marikas Kotopouli 10, 104 32 Athens","phone":"+30 210 523 3637","hours":"Morning–evening","maps":"https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1&query=Stani+galaktopoleio+Omonia+Athens","verdict":"The last true galaktopoleio in central Athens — sheep's-milk yogurt so dense the spoon stands upright, and no one in the centre does it better.","signature":"Sheep's-milk yogurt, honey and walnuts: cool, dense, faintly gamey, under mountain fir honey and crushed walnuts.","caveat":"Not a café to linger in — no espresso ritual, no brunch plates, no laptops; you eat dairy the old way and leave.","person":"Thanasis Karageorgos — third-generation owner, grandson of founder Nikolaos Karageorgos, a Fokida dairyman whose herds and honey suppliers the shop still uses.","signal_chip":{"label":"Fair gold","full":"THESSALONIKI FAIR 1953 — gold medal for its sheep's-milk yogurt","cosign":"and the spoon still stands upright in it."},"dishes":[{"name":"Sheep's-milk yogurt, honey & walnuts","note":"cool, dense, faintly gamey, under mountain fir honey and crushed walnuts","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Anthogalo with honey","note":"milk-flower clotted cream, a glass down a litre and a half of milk, spooned under honey","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Rizogalo","note":"rice pudding from Fokida milk, cooked thick and cinnamon-dusted, made fresh daily","kind":"sweet"},{"name":"Galaktoboureko","note":"warm semolina custard in crisp phyllo, soaked in lemon-scented syrup, cut warm","kind":"sweet"},{"name":"Loukoumades","note":"yeast doughnuts fried to order, drowned in honey and cinnamon","kind":"sweet"},{"name":"Krema cream pudding","note":"cornflour-and-milk pudding, cool and wobbling, dusted with cinnamon","kind":"sweet"},{"name":"Fresh butter & kaimaki cream","note":"mountain-herd butter and thick clotted milk-skin to carry back aboard","kind":"buy"},{"name":"Fresh butter and kaimaki cream","note":"provisioning-worthy dairy to carry back aboard","kind":"buy"}]},
    {"id":"krinos","cat":"shop","tier":"plenty","priority":25,"badge":"Loukoumas","name":"Krinos","short":"Krinos","lat":37.98041,"lng":23.72841,"neighborhood":"Historic centre · Aiolou pedestrian St","tags":["~EUR 4–8 pp","None — marble tables","Mid-morning with a Greek coffee"],"productTags":["Since 1923","Ring loukoumas","Asia-Minor"],"why":"The name belongs to a pharmacist. In 1923 Minas Kasimatis, an Asia Minor refugee, opened his loukoumas house in the Aiolou building where Stamatis Krinos had founded Athens' first pharmacy in 1855 — and kept the old name on the façade. Between the wars it became the meeting point for the city's Asia Minor refugees, and the ring-shaped loukoumas, hole in the middle in the Constantinople style, came south with them. Under the mosaic floor and marble tables, master confectioner Giannis Thalasseles has worked the fryer for over three decades. Heirs of Kasimatis still run it. Athinorama, in May 2026, still called these the most historic loukoumades in Athens.","address":"Aiolou 87, 105 51 Athens","phone":"+30 210 321 6852","hours":"Daytime–early eve","maps":"https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1&query=Krinos+Aiolou+Athens","verdict":"A century on, no loukoumas in Athens has caught up with its honey-syruped, cinnamon-dusted ring.","signature":"Loukoumades me meli: ring-shaped, crisp shell, molten crumb, honey syrup, heavy cinnamon, served scalding.","caveat":"Not for phyllo purists on a bougatsa pilgrimage, and not a lingering brunch room — marble, syrup and speed.","person":"Giannis Thalasseles — master confectioner, over three decades at the fryer; the shop is still run by heirs of founder Minas Kasimatis, an Asia Minor refugee who opened it in 1923.","dishes":[{"name":"Loukoumades me meli","note":"hollow rings, shatter-crisp shell over a molten crumb, drowned in hot honey and heavy cinnamon","kind":"sweet"},{"name":"Loukoumades me sokolata","note":"the same scalding rings, this time run with dark chocolate or hazelnut praline instead of syrup","kind":"sweet"},{"name":"Bougatsa me voutyro","note":"warm layered phyllo, butter soaking through, dusted with icing sugar and cinnamon","kind":"sweet"},{"name":"Greek coffee","note":"briki-brewed, thick and bitter — the correct chaser to all that honey syrup","kind":"drink"},{"name":"Bougatsa me krema","note":"buttery old-Athens square with icing sugar","kind":"sweet"}]},
    {"id":"the-underdog","cat":"shop","tier":"plenty","priority":26,"badge":"Coffee","name":"The Underdog","short":"The Underdog","lat":37.97494,"lng":23.71915,"neighborhood":"Thissio · Irakleidon, off Apostolou Pavlou","tags":["~EUR 15–25 pp brunch","Online booking; walk-ins wait","Weekday 09:00–11:00"],"productTags":["World-champ barista","Micro-roastery","Benchmark brunch"],"why":"A neoclassical shell on Irakleidon, just off the Apostolou Pavlou promenade, became Greece's coffee-competition dynasty. Co-founder Tasos Delichristos took a World Coffee in Good Spirits title in 2008; the house's competition face, Michalis Dimitrakopoulos, won the same world championship in 2016 and reached the World Barista final in 2019. The micro-roastery and brew bar are staged centre-room like an altar, which is the tell: Athens' brunch wave was built by competition baristas, not restaurateurs. Behind the coffee comes a brunch that outdraws most Athens kitchens — chocolate babka on a house starter, generous eggs Benedict. Weekdays it opens at 07:30 and closes by 19:00; no late bar here.","address":"Irakleidon 8, 118 51 Athens","phone":"+30 213 036 5393","hours":"07:30–19:00","maps":"https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1&query=The+Underdog+Irakleidon+Athens","verdict":"Athens' most decorated coffee room also cooks the city's benchmark brunch — and the flat white will still outclass whatever lands on the plate.","signature":"Flat white on the house roast: silky, cocoa-dark, zero bitterness, beside warm chocolate babka.","caveat":"Not for a quiet solo session at peak — weekend brunch is a scrum; but a weekday 08:00 espresso is exactly available.","person":"Michalis Dimitrakopoulos — 2016 World Coffee in Good Spirits Champion and 2019 World Barista finalist, coached to his first world title by Underdog co-founder Tasos Delichristos.","signal_chip":{"label":"World cup","full":"SCA — Michalis Dimitrakopoulos, 2016 World Coffee in Good Spirits Champion & 2019 World Barista finalist","cosign":"and the flat white shows every trophy."},"dishes":[{"name":"Flat white","note":"house-roasted, velvet microfoam, cocoa-dark with almost no bitterness — the cup that shows the trophies","kind":"drink"},{"name":"Single-origin filter","note":"poured from the room's own roaster, bright and near tea-clear, no milk to hide behind","kind":"drink"},{"name":"Coffee in good spirits","note":"espresso built into spirits by the world-champ bar, warm, boozy, a competition specialty","kind":"drink"},{"name":"Chocolate babka","note":"raised on the house sourdough starter, fudgy dark chocolate running every seam","kind":"sweet"},{"name":"Pancakes","note":"stacked fluffy under mascarpone cream, salted caramel, banana and toasted pecans","kind":"sweet"},{"name":"Eggs Benedict","note":"poached eggs over ham on toast, hollandaise loose and lemony, a big weekend plate","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Shakshuka","note":"eggs poached soft in spiced tomato and pepper, mopped up with warm bread","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Avocado toast","note":"smashed avocado on toasted sourdough, chilli and lemon, an egg set on top","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Coffee cocktail","note":"coffee mixed with spirits by the house team","kind":"drink"}]},
    {"id":"oinomageireio-ipeiros","cat":"market","tier":"plenty","priority":27,"badge":"Patsas","name":"Oinomageireio I Ipeiros","short":"Ipeiros","lat":37.98033,"lng":23.72805,"neighborhood":"Varvakios Market · Filopoimenos side, off Athinas","tags":["EUR 8–15 pp","None — share a marble top","07:00–09:00, clubbers meet butchers"],"productTags":["Since 1898","Last in the market","Dawn patsas"],"why":"It has fed the Varvakios meat market since the nineteenth century — the house dates itself to 1898 — and it is the last patsatzidiko standing inside the hall, marble tables set among the hanging carcasses on the Filopoimenos side. In 2023 Vasilis Akrivos, chef of the fish taverna Psariston, took over the cauldrons and kept everything: the white beef patsas, the boiled goat, the Easter offal soup served like a weekday breakfast. One thing changed — the all-night legend now keeps market hours, roughly 07:00 to 18:00. So treat it as the dawn stop, not the 3 a.m. one: clubbers on one bench, butchers in bloodied aprons on the next, the same white soup for both.","address":"Filopoimenos 4, Varvakios Agora, 105 51 Athens","phone":"+30 210 324 0773","hours":"Dawn–18:00","maps":"https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1&query=Oinomageireio+Ipeiros+Varvakios+Athens","verdict":"The last patsatzidiko inside the Varvakios meat market — the Athenian night's official final stop since 1898, now taken at dawn rather than at three.","signature":"White beef patsas: steam fogging the marble, spiked with your own skordostoumpi garlic-vinegar.","caveat":"Not for the 03:00 crowd anymore — it closes late afternoon; and not for anyone squeamish about hanging carcasses at breakfast.","person":"Vasilis Akrivos — chef of the fish taverna Psariston; took over the historic magereio in 2023 and kept the patsas cauldron, the soups and the market kitchen intact.","dishes":[{"name":"Patsas (white, beef)","note":"pale tripe-and-trotter broth, leg and intestine finely chopped; you spike it with garlic-vinegar yourself","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Gida vrasti (boiled goat)","note":"clear broth poured first, then the goat sliding off the bone","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Magiritsa","note":"Easter offal-and-greens soup, egg-lemon thickened, served here on any weekday","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Moschari kokkinisto","note":"beef braised red in tomato from the morning pots, the porters' lunch","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Giouvarlakia avgolemono","note":"rice-studded meatballs in a lemony egg broth, warm and loose in the bowl","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Arni frikase","note":"lamb stewed down with greens under a tart egg-lemon sauce","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Katsiki giouvetsi","note":"goat baked slow with kritharaki orzo, tomato-rich and clinging to the spoon","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Psarosoupa","note":"clear fish soup, the fish-taverna chef's hand, finished with lemon and oil","kind":"dish"}]},
    {"id":"o-makis","cat":"mainland","tier":"plenty","priority":28,"badge":"Patsas","name":"O Makis","short":"O Makis","lat":38.01976,"lng":23.69314,"neighborhood":"Peristeri · Leoforos Thivon, western Athens","tags":["EUR 8–14 pp","None — 24h counter","04:00–06:00 with the night shift"],"productTags":["Since 1994","24/7","Only cauldrons"],"why":"The recipe line runs to Serres, Greece's patsas capital: Makis apprenticed under a master named Odysseas before opening on Leoforos Thivon in 1994. He came from Streffi, a village outside Pyrgos, and still appears nightly even though his sons Thanasis and Charalampos now run the counter. It is the only patsatzidiko in Athens still working big dedicated cauldrons — two hundred portions on an ordinary day, five hundred on a cold one, and a house record of two and a half thousand during the February 2007 snowstorm. The lights are fluorescent, the room is deep in Peristeri, and it closes exactly twenty-four hours a year — Easter Sunday.","address":"Leoforos Thivon 235, Peristeri","phone":"+30 210 577 6136","hours":"24/7","maps":"https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1&query=O+Makis+patsas+Thivon+Peristeri","verdict":"Athens' hardest-working patsas cauldron: hundreds of portions a day, open every hour of the year except Easter Sunday.","signature":"Patsas chontrokommenos: coarse-cut tripe from the cauldron, lashed with garlic-vinegar and scarlet boukovo oil.","caveat":"Not a taverna evening — a fluorescent-lit working canteen deep in Peristeri; tripe-refusers get gyros, not poetry.","person":"Makis — founder (1994), from Streffi outside Pyrgos; learned patsas from Odysseas, a master from Serres, and still appears nightly although sons Thanasis and Charalampos now run it.","dishes":[{"name":"Patsas chontrokommenos (coarse-cut)","note":"coarse belly cut straight from the cauldron, lashed with garlic-vinegar and scarlet pepper oil","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Patsas psilokommenos (fine-cut)","note":"fine-chopped tripe, silkier spoonfuls, the easier first road in for beginners","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Podia (trotters)","note":"boneless trotters simmered to gelatin, sticky and rich beside the tripe","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Kotosoupa","note":"clear chicken broth from the same cauldrons, the gentle 4 a.m. option","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Moscharosoupa","note":"beef broth with vegetables, deep and restoring after a night shift","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Makaronia me kima","note":"pasta under tomato mince, for the ones who came for the grill, not the tripe","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Grills and gyros","note":"the psitopoleio side, charcoal gyros for companions who refuse the cauldron","kind":"dish"}]},
    {"id":"bougatsadiko-thessaloniki","cat":"shop","tier":"plenty","priority":29,"badge":"Bougatsa","name":"Bougatsadiko I Thessaloniki stou Psyrri","short":"Bougatsadiko Thessaloniki","lat":37.97843,"lng":23.72492,"neighborhood":"Psyrri · Plateia Iroon corner, at Miaouli","tags":["EUR 4–8 pp","None — counter and square","Weekend dawn, 05:00–07:00"],"productTags":["Hand-opened phyllo","Weekend 24h","Dawn bougatsa"],"why":"Thessaloniki's bougatsa craft transplanted whole into the heart of Athens' night quarter: on Plateia Iroon, at the corner of Miaouli, the dough is opened by hand on a marble slab in the shop window while you wait. The owner, Natasa, works from recipes her grandfather carried down from Thessaloniki. Heroes' Square gives it the one thing the northern dawn bougatsatzidika have always had — a clientele that hasn't slept yet. Cream, minced meat or salty cheese, buried under cinnamon and icing sugar. Sunday to Thursday it runs to around two in the morning; Friday and Saturday the pans never stop for a full twenty-four hours.","address":"Plateia Iroon 1, 105 54 Athens","phone":"+30 210 322 2088","hours":"Dawn–02:00; Fri–Sat 24h","maps":"https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1&query=Bougatsadiko+Thessaloniki+Plateia+Iroon+Athens","verdict":"Psyrri's dawn bougatsa: hand-opened phyllo on Heroes' Square, and on weekends the pans do not stop for twenty-four hours.","signature":"Bougatsa me krema: warm custard, shattering phyllo, buried under cinnamon and icing sugar at dawn.","caveat":"Not a refined patisserie — square-side chairs, bar-crowd noise; and midweek the shutters come down around 02:00.","person":"Owner Natasa, whose grandfather brought the bougatsa recipes down from Thessaloniki; the phyllo is still opened by hand on marble in the window.","dishes":[{"name":"Bougatsa me krema","note":"warm semolina custard between shattering leaves of hand-pulled phyllo, dusted heavy with cinnamon and icing sugar","kind":"sweet"},{"name":"Bougatsa me kima","note":"spiced beef mince folded hot into crackling phyllo, black pepper and a breath of cinnamon","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Bougatsa me tyri","note":"salty feta melting inside crisp layered pastry, cut with scissors — the worker's dawn plate","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Bougatsa me spanaki","note":"wilted spinach and sharp feta under blistered phyllo, greener and less sweet","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Kreatopita","note":"chunkier meat pie, minced beef and onion sealed in oil-brushed layered dough","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Elliniko / freddo espresso","note":"thick unfiltered coffee or a cold freddo — the bitter foil to all that sugar at 5am","kind":"drink"}]},
    {"id":"elvis","cat":"shop","tier":"plenty","priority":30,"badge":"Kalamaki","name":"Elvis","short":"Elvis","lat":37.98111,"lng":23.71645,"neighborhood":"Kerameikos · Plataion & Leonidou corner","tags":["EUR 5–10 pp","None — counter and stools","Late, after the Kerameikos bars"],"productTags":["Kalamaki only","No wraps","Late-night"],"why":"An old corner butcher's shop on Plataion kept the name 'Elvis' from its days as the set of a TV series, and Spyros Athanasiou and Vangelis Petridis turned it into the city's definitive late-night kalamaki counter. There are no wraps and barely any chairs — bare pork skewers off the charcoal, grilled pita on the side, hand-cut fries, a beer, rockabilly on the speakers, meat cut like a butcher still owns the room. Order by the skewer, not by the wrap. The Kerameikos original runs from midday to around three in the morning, Fridays and Saturdays to five — this is the night-owls' skewer, at its best after the neighbourhood's bars empty.","address":"Plataion 29 & Leonidou, 104 35 Athens","phone":"+30 210 345 5836","hours":"Midday–03:00; Fri–Sat 05:00","maps":"https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1&query=Elvis+kalamakia+Kerameikos+Athens","verdict":"The Athenian kalamaki needs nothing but salt, charcoal and midnight — leave without ordering a second round of skewers and we got it wrong.","signature":"Pork kalamaki, by the pair: salt, char and juice, with grilled pita quarters and a beer.","caveat":"Not for wrap-seekers, daylight romantics or anyone needing a table — a butcher's-corner counter that peaks after midnight.","person":"Spyros Athanasiou and Vangelis Petridis — turned an old Plataion butcher's shop, which kept the name 'Elvis' from its TV-set days, into the city's definitive late-night kalamaki counter.","dishes":[{"name":"Pork kalamaki, by the pair","note":"bare pork shoulder off the charcoal — salt, char and running juice, no wrap, no sauce","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Chicken kalamaki","note":"marinated thigh charred at the edges, lemon-bright and softer than the pork","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Keftedes skewer","note":"loose herbed pork-and-beef meatballs, cumin and oregano, threaded on the stick","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Loukaniko me prasa","note":"coarse pork sausage cut with sweet leek, blistered and split open on the grill","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Panceta (marinated pork belly)","note":"fatty belly rendered crisp at the edges, cut into charred, glistening ribbons","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Grilled corn pita","note":"smoky corn-flour pita blackened over the coals, torn and used as cutlery","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Hand-cut fries","note":"potatoes cut and fried to order, hot and salted, vinegar-sharp when asked","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Cold beer","note":"a sweating bottle of lager, the only right thing to drink against the char","kind":"drink"}]},
    {"id":"karamanlidika-tou-fani","cat":"shop","tier":"plenty","priority":31,"badge":"Pastourma","name":"Ta Karamanlidika tou Fani","short":"Karamanlidika","lat":37.98014,"lng":23.72569,"neighborhood":"Psyrri edge · Sokratous & Evripidou, by Varvakios market","tags":["EUR 20-25 pp","Book — peak waits; rooftop tables go first","Lunch after the Varvakios market walk"],"productTags":["Since 2014","Pastourma row","Galley-packs"],"why":"The name honours the Karamanlides — Turkish-speaking Orthodox Christians of Cappadocia who printed Greek in Ottoman script and came west in the 1923 exchange. Fanis Theodoropoulos, a second-generation charcutier who kept shop on Evripidou's old pastourma row, opened this deli-meze in spring 2014 with pastirma-maker Paraskevas Sarimpoyias of Sary, in Drama. Half the restored neoclassical is a counter of cured meat, half a table; the front vacuum-packs pastourma and soutzouki that survive a week in a galley fridge. It deliberately revives the interwar pastourmatzidika, where refugee curers first taught Athens the smell of fenugreek.","address":"Sokratous 1 & Evripidou 52, 105 52 Athens","phone":"+30 210 325 4184","hours":"Mon-Sat 09:00-23:00; Sun closed","maps":"https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1&query=Ta+Karamanlidika+tou+Fani+Athens","verdict":"The pastourma pie and the deli counter alone justify crossing town; everything past the cured-meat canon is merely good.","signature":"Pastourma pie: fenugreek-crusted cured beef and molten cheese in crackling hot phyllo","caveat":"Not for vegetarians or the cumin-averse, and dark on Sundays.","person":"Fanis Theodoropoulos — second-generation charcutier from Evripidou's pastourma row; opened the deli-meze in spring 2014 with pastirma-maker Paraskevas Sarimpoyias of Sary, Drama.","signal_chip":{"label":"Ath. '19","full":"Athinorama 2018 & 2019 — Greek Cuisine tribute pick","cosign":"and the pastourma pie earns the trip on its own"},"dishes":[{"name":"Karamanli pastourma platter","note":"paper-thin mahogany slices under a rust-red cumin-and-fenugreek tsimeni crust","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Pastourma with eggs","note":"country eggs set soft over tomato and smoky cured beef, cumin rising off the pan","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Grilled soutzouki","note":"garlic-heavy horseshoe sausage blistered and split off the grill, laid on warm pita","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Isli kefte","note":"fried egg-shaped patties of minced beef and bulgur, crisp shell over a warm spiced centre","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Mommy's dolmades","note":"hand-rolled vine leaves, lemon-sharp herbed rice, served cool with a spoon of yogurt","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Kavourma me piperies","note":"confit preserved beef warmed loose with sweet bell peppers and soft potato","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Mommy's Arcadian baklava","note":"layered flaky phyllo, buttered walnut, heavy and slow with syrup","kind":"sweet"},{"name":"Vacuum-packed pastourma","note":"cut to order at the front counter, fenugreek-sealed, survives a week's charter fridge","kind":"buy"}]},
    {"id":"miran","cat":"shop","tier":"plenty","priority":32,"badge":"1922 deli","name":"Miran","short":"Miran","lat":37.97995,"lng":23.72568,"neighborhood":"Market quarter · Evripidou spice street","tags":["Deli — pay by weight; counter tasting plates","No booking — a shop with a tasting corner","Late morning, spice trade in full cry"],"productTags":["Since 1922","4 generations","At-source cure"],"why":"Miran Kourounlian, an Armenian refugee from Caesarea — Kayseri, in Cappadocia — fled via Constantinople and Chios and landed in Piraeus, where in 1922 he began salting beef into pastourma; the narrow Evripidou shop followed. Interwar Athenians, hit by the tsimeni's strange perfume of cumin and fenugreek, swore the cured meat was camel. Four generations on, his grandsons Miran and Krikor still cure on the same spice street, their father Berdos having industrialised production in 1983. It is a shop, not a taverna — a renovated counter with a tasting corner where charcuterie boards come with tsipouro amid the market's noise.","address":"Evripidou 45, 105 54 Athens","phone":"+30 210 321 7187","hours":"Shop hours; closed Sun — call ahead","maps":"https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1&query=Miran+Pastourma+Evripidou+Athens","verdict":"No shop in Athens sells better pastourma, and the standing counter-tasting outclasses most sit-down meze in the quarter.","signature":"Aged veal pastourma: paper-thin mahogany slices under a faintly bitter mustard-yellow tsimeni crust","caveat":"Not a restaurant — no full meals, no evening hours, strictly carnivore territory.","person":"Miran and Krikor Kourounlian — grandsons of founder Miran, an Armenian refugee from Kayseri who began curing pastourma in Piraeus in 1922; father Berdos industrialised it in 1983.","dishes":[{"name":"Armenian soutzouk","note":"dry spiced sausage rings, garlic-deep and firm, cut thin and built for red wine","kind":"buy"},{"name":"Counter tasting board","note":"pastourma, soutzouki and cheese with a shot of tsipouro amid the spice-street noise","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Avga me pastourma","note":"country eggs fried soft in the pan with freshly-shaved cumin-red beef pastourma","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Peinirli me pastourma","note":"a boat of oven-hot dough, melted cheese and pastourma laid in at the last minute","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Armenian kebab","note":"minced-beef kebab off the fire, Kayseri spicing, straight from grill to plate","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Beef lahmatzoun","note":"thin crackling flatbread under minced beef, tomato and pepper, rolled to eat by hand","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Kavourma","note":"beef or buffalo confit set in its own fat, jarred — warms into eggs or beans","kind":"buy"},{"name":"Rarity pastourmas","note":"turkey, buffalo, smoked beef tongue or a without-tsimeni cure — ask what's cut fresh","kind":"buy"}]},
    {"id":"to-aigyptiakon","cat":"mainland","tier":"plenty","priority":33,"badge":"1st kebab","name":"To Aigyptiakon","short":"To Aigyptiakon","lat":37.97308,"lng":23.66019,"neighborhood":"Nikaia (Piraeus) · Petrou Ralli, old Kokkinia","tags":["EUR 10-18 pp (est.)","Walk-in; phone ahead for groups","Right at the 17:00 opening, before the queue"],"productTags":["Since 1924","Greece's 1st kebab","Refugee Nikaia"],"why":"Nikaia rose in 1923 as a refugee city on Piraeus's red earth — Nea Kokkinia, 5,584 houses raised between 1926 and 1930 — and it was here, not central Athens, that Greeks first met kebab. Misak Anispikian, an Armenian from Adana who escaped through Egypt (hence 'The Egyptian') and Hellenised his name to Isaak Meraklides, opened the country's first kebaptzidiko in 1924 and swapped the Arabic flatbread for Greek pita. His fourth-generation namesake now works the charcoal; his wife Dimitra makes the falafel and sweets. In 2023 the National Hellenic Research Foundation mounted its 'Century of Displacements' show on the premises.","address":"Petrou Ralli 168, 184 54 Nikaia","phone":"+30 210 418 2920","hours":"Mon-Sat 17:00-24:00; Sun closed","maps":"https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1&query=To+Aigyptiakon+Nikaia+Piraeus","verdict":"Greece's first kebab house, grilling since 1924, still makes one of its best — worth the ride from the port on a Saturday evening.","signature":"Kebab yogurtlou: charcoal-grilled hand-minced kebab on pita under warm tomato, sumac and yogurt","caveat":"Not central and not scenic — a working-class Nikaia avenue, dinner-only, zero frills.","person":"Misak Anispikian — fourth generation and namesake of the 1924 founder; his wife Dimitra makes the falafel, salads and sweets.","signal_chip":{"label":"LiFO 2021","full":"LiFO 2021 — profiled as one of Greece's best kebabs","cosign":"and it's the country's first kebab house, since 1924"},"dishes":[{"name":"Adana kebab in pita","note":"spicy hand-minced lamb off the charcoal, charred at the edges, chilli-flecked, folded hot in Greek pita","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Falafel","note":"green-hearted, crisp-shelled chickpea fritters, cumin-warm, Dimitra's nod to the Egypt years","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Lahmacun","note":"paper-thin flatbread under spiced mince, rolled around parsley and a hard squeeze of lemon","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Charcoal tiropita","note":"cheese pie blistered over the coals, molten and salty inside its crackling shell","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Pumpkin kefte wrap (kolokithokeftedes)","note":"warm squash-and-herb fritters, sweet and crisp-edged, wrapped with yogurt and raw onion","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Kebab sketo (beef-and-lamb skewer)","note":"hand-minced beef and lamb grilled over charcoal, juicy, salt-and-cumin, no chilli this time","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Sumac onions with parsley","note":"raw onion tumbled with sumac and parsley, cool and sharp against the char","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Ayran","note":"cold salted yogurt drink, thin and tart, cutting the smoke and the chilli","kind":"drink"},{"name":"Lahmajun","note":"thin flatbread, spiced mince, rolled with lemon","kind":"dish"}]},
    {"id":"peran-kafe-aman","cat":"mainland","tier":"plenty","priority":34,"badge":"Café aman","name":"Peran, to Kafe Aman","short":"Peran","lat":38.02842,"lng":23.73372,"neighborhood":"Nea Chalkidona · Dekeleias, northern refugee belt","tags":["EUR 25-30 pp","Book on live-music nights","Fri/Sat night for sets; Sun afternoon for lunch"],"productTags":["Politiki kouzina","Live cafe aman","House-baked"],"why":"Named for Pera, the European quarter of Constantinople, and set in Nea Chalkidona — a suburb the refugees named for Chalcedon across the Bosphorus. It revives the cafe aman: the improvised-song coffeehouse the uprooted of 1922 carried west, where a singer throws out a line and the room answers 'aman, aman'. Appetisers are chosen off a passing tray, Constantinople-style; the bread and the syrup sweets are baked in the stone-walled room. Wednesday to Saturday it fills for the live sets, Sunday afternoon for a long Politiki family lunch.","address":"Dekeleias 20, 143 43 Nea Chalkidona","phone":"+30 210 253 3896","hours":"Wed-Sat 19:00-02:00; Sun 13:00-20:00","maps":"https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1&query=Peran+to+Kafe+Aman+Nea+Chalkidona","verdict":"The last politiki-kouzina table standing in Athinorama's guide, and the live cafe-aman nights alone justify crossing the refugee belt.","signature":"Yogurt kebab with cumin: juicy, gently spicy, bleeding into the house-baked bread","caveat":"Not a quick stop — music nights run long and loud, and it's closed Monday to Wednesday lunch.","signal_chip":{"label":"Ath. 2026","full":"Athinorama 2026 — the guide's only politiki-kouzina table","cosign":"and we'd cross the refugee belt for the cafe-aman nights"},"dishes":[{"name":"Meze tray selection","note":"small cold plates chosen off a passing platter, old-Pera manners, sharp and shared","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Hunkar begendi","note":"braised beef sinking into smoked-eggplant cream under a cap of melted cheese","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Lahmacun","note":"thin wood-oven flatbread under spiced mince, rolled hot around parsley and lemon","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Manti","note":"tiny meat dumplings under cool garlic yogurt and a spoon of paprika butter","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Ali Nazik Urfa","note":"spiced lamb over warm smoked-eggplant and garlic-yogurt purée, smoky and soft","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Kotopoulo doner","note":"shaved chicken off the vertical spit, crisp-edged, juicy under its own dripping fat","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Tabouleh","note":"cracked bulgur with tomato and parsley, cold and lemon-sharp, slick with olive oil","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Kunefe","note":"shredded kadaifi over unsweetened cheese, baked hot in syrup, stretching under crushed pistachio","kind":"sweet"},{"name":"House Politiki sweets","note":"syrup-soaked, baked in the shop like the bread","kind":"sweet"}]},
    {"id":"kostas-agia-irini","cat":"shop","tier":"plenty","priority":35,"badge":"Souvlaki","name":"Kostas (Agia Irini)","short":"Kostas","lat":37.97712,"lng":23.72834,"neighborhood":"Monastiraki · Plateia Agias Eirinis, by the church","tags":["EUR 3–7 pp","None — stand in the queue","Before the 13:00 office wave"],"productTags":["Since 1946","EUR 3 wrap","Secret sauce"],"why":"The story every Athenian tells: since 1946 this closet-sized counter beside the church of Agia Eirini has wrapped souvlaki in pillowy pita with finely chopped tomato and a red sauce made to a recipe nobody has managed to extract — offered hot, medium or sweet, the hot one nicknamed 'the medicine'. In February 2025 the wrap was still three euros. The queue is the square's daily clock, running from late morning; when the day's meat ends, the shutter drops and the square loses its lunch. Do not confuse it with the unrelated 'since 1950' Kostas over on Filellinon. Standing room only; carry cash.","address":"Plateia Agias Eirinis 2, 105 60 Athens","phone":"+30 210 323 2971","hours":"Late morning till sold out","maps":"https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1&query=Kostas+Plateia+Agias+Eirinis+Athens","verdict":"The three-euro wrap from this postwar hole-in-the-wall still beats every chef-built souvlaki in Athens — arrive after 15:00 and the meat is likely gone.","signature":"Souvlaki me ap'ola, hot sauce: charred pork, chopped tomato, the fiery house 'farmako' red.","caveat":"Not for sit-down comfort or late lunches — no tables, and no mercy once the day's meat is finished.","dishes":[{"name":"Souvlaki me ap'ola, hot sauce","note":"charred pork, chopped tomato and the fiery house 'farmako' red in pillowy pita","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Kalamaki sketo","note":"the bare pork skewer, salt, pepper and lemon, judged with nothing to hide","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Bifteki wrap, medium sauce","note":"loose-grained beef patty, sweeter sauce, softer chew, folded in warm pita","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Souvlaki, sweet sauce","note":"same charred pork and tomato under the mild sweet red, for those who skip the 'medicine'","kind":"dish"}]},
    {"id":"hoocut","cat":"shop","tier":"plenty","priority":36,"badge":"Souvlaki","name":"Hoocut","short":"Hoocut","lat":37.97683,"lng":23.72808,"neighborhood":"Monastiraki · Plateia Agias Eirinis 9, at Aiolou","tags":["~EUR 8–14 pp","None — order at counter","Off-peak 15:00–18:00"],"productTags":["Since 2018","Five chefs","Chef's pick"],"why":"Three years after they opened the acclaimed Cookoovaya, five of its chefs — Periklis Koskinas, Nikos Karathanos, Kleomenis Zournatzis and the Liakos brothers, Spyros and Vangelis — took on the hardest test in Greek cooking, the street's own dish, and built a vertical souvlaki house on Agia Irini square in January 2018. Bakery, butcher's line and greengrocer work in view; the pita is kneaded and baked metres from the grill, and the meat comes from Metameat, a plant they built to supply the shop alone. The name welds the butcher's 'hook' to the 'cut'. Thirty metres away, old Kostas sells the three-euro classic — the square now stages the whole souvlaki argument in fifty metres.","address":"Plateia Agias Eirinis 9, 105 63 Athens","phone":"+30 210 324 0026","hours":"12:00–23:30","maps":"https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1&query=Hoocut+Agias+Eirinis+Athens","verdict":"Five acclaimed chefs run Athens' most disciplined souvlaki, and a Michelin-starred peer calls it 'as genuine as it gets' — the pita out of the oven proves both.","signature":"Pork-belly pita: crackling edge, molten fat and bright raw onion on bread baked metres away.","caveat":"Costs more than a corner souvlatzidiko and there's no table service — nostalgics for the three-euro paper-wrapped classic should walk thirty metres to Kostas.","person":"The five chefs of Cookoovaya — Periklis Koskinas, Nikos Karathanos, Kleomenis Zournatzis and the Liakos brothers Spyros & Vangelis — opened Hoocut in Jan 2018 and built Metameat, a meat plant that supplies the shop exclusively.","signal_chip":{"label":"Chef pick","full":"THIS IS ATHENS 2026 — CTC's Alexandros Tsiotinis: 'as genuine as it gets, as clean as it should be today'","cosign":"and the house-baked pita proves both halves."},"dishes":[{"name":"Pork belly pita","note":"crackling-edged belly, molten fat and raw onion on pita baked metres away","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Lamb pita","note":"diced lamb, drippy and clean, cabbage and paprika folded in house-baked pita","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Beef short-rib pita","note":"slow-cooked rib meat, deep and dark, richer than any gyros","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Hand-cut fries","note":"twice-cooked, crisp outside and fluffy in, meant to share on the square","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Black-pig sausage pita","note":"coarse black-pig sausage with honey-mustard and cabbage, snapping under house-baked pita","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Chicken pita","note":"shaved chicken thigh off the spit, crisp-edged and juicy, tzatziki and tomato","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Squid pita","note":"griddled squid with taramosalata and spring onion, cool and briny in warm pita","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Dolmades pita","note":"handmade vine-leaf dolmades, lemony and herb-packed, folded meatless into fresh-baked pita","kind":"dish"}]},
    {"id":"o-thanasis","cat":"shop","tier":"plenty","priority":37,"badge":"Kebab","name":"O Thanasis","short":"O Thanasis","lat":37.97626,"lng":23.72636,"neighborhood":"Monastiraki · Mitropoleos, at the square's mouth","tags":["EUR 10–15 pp","None — first come","Off-peak 17:00–19:00, or after midnight"],"productTags":["Since 1964","Charcoal kebab","Kebab war"],"why":"On the corner of Mitropoleos where Ottoman Athens once ground its spices, a decades-old kebab war has run without a truce: O Thanasis, founded in 1964 by two cousins from Ioannina, against Bairaktaris across the street, family-run since 1879. Thanasis' weapon has never changed — hand-formed lamb-and-beef mince grilled on charcoal, laid on pita with raw onion, tomato and a dust of paprika, no fries needed. This is the legendary kebab of Monastiraki, an oblong charcoal cylinder, not a skewer souvlaki; order accordingly. Athenians treat their allegiance to one side or the other as a minor article of identity. The daily lunch line is part of the ritual.","address":"Mitropoleos 69, 105 55 Athens","phone":"+30 210 324 4705","hours":"10:00–02:00","maps":"https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1&query=O+Thanasis+Mitropoleos+Athens","verdict":"Since 1964, 'kebab' in Athens has meant this exact spiced, charcoal-grilled cylinder at Mitropoleos 69 — still the centre's most dependable plate after midnight.","signature":"Kebab merida on pita: charcoal-charred lamb-beef mince with raw onion, tomato and a paprika dust.","caveat":"Not for anyone chasing quiet or the bare pork kalamaki — a loud, touristic, table-service kebab institution, and that is the point.","person":"Founded 1964 by two cousins from Ioannina — a family charcoal-kebab house locked in a decades-old 'kebab war' with Bairaktaris (family-run since 1879) across the street.","dishes":[{"name":"Kebab merida on pita","note":"hand-formed lamb-beef mince, charcoal-charred and smoky, on warm pita with raw onion and paprika dust","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Yogourtlou kebab","note":"the charred cylinder blanketed in cool thick strained yogurt, paprika-butter pooling over the top","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Pork souvlaki pita","note":"skewered pork shoulder off the charcoal, wrapped in soft pita with tomato, onion and tzatziki","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Gyros pita","note":"spit-shaved pork, crisp-edged and juicy, rolled in pita with onion, fries and tzatziki","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Saganaki","note":"kefalograviera fried till the crust blisters, edges lace-crisp, lemon squeezed over the melt","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Horiatiki","note":"tomato, cucumber and onion under a slab of feta, oregano and green olive oil","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Roasted peppers + tzatziki","note":"sweet charred peppers in oil beside cold, garlic-thick strained-yogurt tzatziki","kind":"dish"},{"name":"House red in a small jug","note":"rough young red, served cold by the jug, cutting the charred fat","kind":"drink"},{"name":"Kebab me yiaourti","note":"yogurt-slicked version, cooling against the spice","kind":"dish"}]},
    {"id":"klimataria","cat":"shop","tier":"plenty","priority":38,"badge":"Rebetiko","name":"Klimataria","short":"Klimataria","lat":37.98109,"lng":23.72476,"neighborhood":"Plateia Theatrou · on the square, under the vine","tags":["EUR 20-35 pp (music nights higher)","Book for music nights","Fri/Sat ~22:30; Sunday lunch for the pots"],"productTags":["Since 1927","Live rebetiko","Barrel wine"],"why":"Open since 1927 on the square that gave it its name, with wine barrels for a back wall and the namesake vine overhead. House lore — and the Greek Gastronomy Guide — holds that the great interwar rebetes passed through when this quarter was the city's working heart, Markos Vamvakaris among them, the Syros coal-lugger who formed Piraeus's Famous Quartet in 1934. A century on the formula is untouched: mageirefta cooked by hand, musicians playing from memory, no amplifier worship, palms keeping the zeibekiko's time. Wednesday to Saturday the compania warms up around 22:30; Sunday belongs to the pots.","address":"Plateia Theatrou 2, 105 52 Athens","phone":"+30 210 3216629","hours":"Daily 12:00-02:00; music Wed-Sat","maps":"https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1&query=Klimataria+Plateia+Theatrou+Athens","verdict":"The last taverna in central Athens where barrel wine, hand-cooked mageirefta and live rebetes still share one 1927 room several nights a week.","signature":"Lamb kotsi melomeno: honey-glazed shank collapsing off the bone into its own juices","caveat":"Not a quiet dinner on music nights — after 22:00 conversation surrenders to the band; on off-nights you find only the kitchen.","signal_chip":{"label":"Athens V.","full":"Athens Voice 2024 — 'the emblematic taverna of Plateia Theatrou'","cosign":"and the barrel wine still proves it"},"dishes":[{"name":"Soutzoukakia","note":"cumin-and-garlic Smyrna meatballs simmered soft in a dark, clove-warm tomato sauce","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Giouvetsi","note":"orzo baked mahogany in meat juices, clay-pot edges caramelised, served bubbling","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Gigantes plaki","note":"butter-soft giant beans baked slow in sweet tomato and oil, dill scattered over","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Gemista","note":"tomatoes and peppers stuffed with herbed rice, oven-slumped, their juices and oil pooling at the base","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Kokoras krasatos","note":"free-range rooster braised dark in red wine, the meat sliding off the bone over pasta","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Hunkar begendi","note":"veal in tomato ladled over a smoked-eggplant and cheese puree — the 'sultan's delight'","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Handmade pies and bread","note":"in-house leavened bread and hand-rolled pies torn warm, built for mopping sauce","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Barrel wine","note":"young house wine, cold, poured by the kilo jug","kind":"drink"}]},
    {"id":"taverna-tou-oikonomou","cat":"shop","tier":"plenty","priority":39,"badge":"Mageireio","name":"Taverna tou Oikonomou","short":"Tou Oikonomou","lat":37.96969,"lng":23.71323,"neighborhood":"Ano Petralona · Troon & Kydantidon, opposite Zefyros cinema","tags":["EUR 20-25 pp excl. wine","Book weekends — pavement tables go first","Summer evening outside, Zefyros flickering opposite"],"productTags":["Since 1930","Mageireio","Same cook 25yr"],"why":"Giorgos Oikonomou opened a butcher's shop with a single cooking pot in 1930; his son Nikos took over in 1950, and the counter only fully surrendered to the dining room in the early 1970s. When two young owners took the keys in 2023, their first public promise was that nothing change — 'neither the environment nor the food' — so Garoufallia, twenty-five years the cook, and her recipes stayed, along with the old tables and the wall paintings. It is a mageireio: the day's pots run out and service ends. Across the lane flickers Zefyros, one of Athens's oldest open-air cinemas.","address":"Troon 41 & Kydantidon, 118 51 Athens","phone":"+30 210 3467555","hours":"Weekdays from 19:00; weekends from 12:30","maps":"https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1&query=Taverna+tou+Oikonomou+Ano+Petralona","verdict":"The 1930 butcher's-taverna where Athens still measures what home-stewed rooster and hilopites should taste like.","signature":"Rooster with hilopites: wine-dark bird over egg noodles drinking the slow-cooked sauce","caveat":"Not for grill-seekers or late arrivals — the glory is in the pots, and the pots empty.","person":"Garoufallia — the cook, twenty-five years in this kitchen; when the taverna changed hands in 2023 the new owners' first decision was that she and her recipes stay.","signal_chip":{"label":"FNL Guide","full":"FNL Guide — 'a journey into the memory of Greek tradition'","cosign":"and Garoufallia's pots deliver it"},"dishes":[{"name":"Rabbit stifado","note":"rabbit braised down with a mound of whole sweet pearl onions, vinegar and clove depth","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Soutzoukakia","note":"cumin-perfumed meatballs in a bread-mopping tomato sauce, sharp with garlic","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Lamb in the oven","note":"lamb roasted slow with potatoes gone golden in the drippings, oregano over the top","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Summer okra and beans","note":"okra and green beans stewed soft in olive oil and tomato, served at room temperature","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Spanakopita","note":"hand-rolled greens-and-feta pie, thin crust shattering, dill and spinach steaming inside","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Fava","note":"warm yellow split-pea puree topped with raw onion and a thread of green oil","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Moschari me melitzanes","note":"beef stewed until it flakes, over collapsed eggplant in a cinnamon-touched tomato sauce","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Dolmadakia","note":"vine leaves rolled tight around herbed rice, lemon-bright, served cool in their oil","kind":"dish"}]},
    {"id":"margaro","cat":"mainland","tier":"plenty","priority":40,"badge":"5 dishes","name":"Margaro","short":"Margaro","lat":37.93475,"lng":23.62923,"neighborhood":"Piraeus, Hatzikyriakio · Naval Cadets' School gate","tags":["EUR 25-30 pp; ~EUR 40 feeds two","No reservations — go off-peak","Weekday lunch ~13:00; Sunday noon queues"],"productTags":["Since 1944","5-dish menu","By the fryer"],"why":"In 1944 grandmother Margaro Chanioti, from Ano Mera on Mykonos, set her tables opposite the Naval Cadets' School gate and decided a fish taverna needs only what the fryer does perfectly. Four or five things, recited, never printed: red mullet, shrimp, langoustines when the boats deliver, a tomato salad, house white by the kilo. Her Chaniotis descendants — the son now near ninety, with his four children — have not expanded the spoken menu in eighty years. There is no dessert and no sea view; there is a queue of Piraeus families every Sunday noon, and the cadets' flag ceremony across the street at dusk.","address":"Hatzikyriakou 126, 185 39 Piraeus","phone":"+30 210 4514226","hours":"Mon & Wed-Sat 12:00-24:00; Sun 12:30-18:30; closed Tue","maps":"https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1&query=Margaro+Piraeus","verdict":"Eighty years on, a recited menu of five fried things still beats every printed seafood carte in Piraeus.","signature":"Fried barbounia: flour-whispered red mullet, scalding hot, sweet flesh under crackling skin","caveat":"Not for menu-browsers, vegetarians, bookers, or anyone who needs dessert and a sea view.","person":"Margaro Chanioti — Mykonian grandmother from Ano Mera who founded the taverna in 1944; the Chaniotis family still runs the room she named.","signal_chip":{"label":"Ath. 2025","full":"Athinorama 2025 re-review — 'the old neighbourhood fish taverna still lives'","cosign":"and the fryer proves it eighty years on"},"dishes":[{"name":"Fried barbounia (red mullet)","note":"flour-whispered red mullet fried scalding, sweet flesh loosening under crackling skin, lemon only","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Fried garides (shrimp)","note":"shell-on, crisp outside and juicy within, eaten whole with a lemon squeeze","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Karavides (langoustines)","note":"sweet and firm, fried only when the boats deliver — ask, don't expect","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Tomato salad","note":"chunky village tomato in oil, the only vegetable in the house","kind":"dish"},{"name":"House white by the kilo","note":"cold, anonymous, exactly right against the fryer's fried fish","kind":"drink"}]},
    {"id":"dourabeis","cat":"mainland","tier":"plenty","priority":41,"badge":"Est. 1932","name":"Dourabeis","short":"Dourabeis","lat":37.94132,"lng":23.66203,"neighborhood":"Piraeus · Akti Dilaveri, foot of Kastella","tags":["Fish by the kilo; budget EUR 60+ pp","Book — generations fill it","Winter Sunday lunch, the classicists' hour"],"productTags":["Since 1932","3 generations","Island boats"],"why":"Open since 1932 on the same waterside spot below Kastella hill, with porthole windows and framed 1950s Faliro photographs, Dourabeis stopped being a taverna decades ago — this is a white-linen fish house at serious-restaurant prices. The third generation of the founding family still buys the way the first did: wild fish landed for them from Kythira, Evia, Koroni, the Cyclades and Crete, then grilled over charcoal and dressed with nothing but ladolemono. The house calls itself the only one in Attica with its name. Generations of Athenians have eaten here their whole lives.","address":"Akti Dilaveri 29, 185 33 Piraeus","phone":"+30 210 4122092","hours":"Lunch & dinner — call","maps":"https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1&query=Dourabeis+Piraeus","verdict":"Ninety-plus years of charcoal and ladolemono make it the control experiment for every Athens fish kitchen — the plainest possible plate, done better.","signature":"Charcoal-grilled wild fish with ladolemono: salt-sweetness and smoke, dressed old-school, chosen by the kilo","caveat":"Not cheap and not a taverna lark — white-linen fish-house gravity, priced to match.","signal_chip":{"label":"FNL Guide","full":"FNL Guide — 'reference point of classic Athenian fish-eating'","cosign":"and every rival is measured against it"},"dishes":[{"name":"Kakavia","note":"A small cup of amber rockfish broth to open the meal, olive-oil sheen on top.","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Sea urchin (achinos)","note":"Cold orange tongues scooped from the shell, iodine-sweet, loosened with nothing but raw olive oil.","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Crayfish sashimi (karavida)","note":"Raw crayfish tail, translucent and sweet, olive oil drizzled, its own coral eggs alongside.","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Red-mullet ceviche (barbouni)","note":"Thin cold slices cured just to firmness, citrus-bright under a slick of green oil.","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Grilled scallops","note":"Charred at the edges, sweet and yielding, a warm lemon sauce pooled beneath.","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Fried monkfish with beetroot skordalia","note":"Firm sweet cubes fried crisp, set over a crimson beetroot-and-garlic purée, sharp underneath.","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Taramosalata","note":"Whipped pale and airy with olive oil, roe-salt and lemon, bread to drag through.","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Steamed mussels","note":"Opened in lemon, oil and a bite of chili, the broth left to spoon up.","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Dourabeis salad","note":"the house salad, a fixture since forever","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Linguine with oysters","note":"third generation's discreet modern flourish","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Shellfish selection","note":"unusually wide for a classic house — ask what's alive","kind":"dish"}]},
    {"id":"zefyros","cat":"mainland","tier":"plenty","priority":42,"badge":"Est. 1931","name":"Zefyros","short":"Zefyros","lat":37.93887,"lng":23.6606,"neighborhood":"Piraeus · Mikrolimano quay, deck over the water","tags":["View-priced; fish by the kilo","Book the waterside deck ahead","Dusk on the deck, Kastella lighting up"],"productTags":["Since 1931","Mikrolimano's oldest","Deck over water"],"why":"Zefyros opened in 1931, when the cove was still called Tourkolimano, and it was — by Athinorama's 2016 reckoning — Mikrolimano's first fish shop; its 2025 features now call it simply the oldest, ninety-four years and counting. The wooden deck, built out over the water 'like a ship's deck ready for a voyage', still stands directly above the harbour. The cooking has never chased fashion: whole day-boat fish grilled plainly, oysters opened to order, a wine list that now leans Greek. Above the deck, Kastella's amphitheatre of shipowners' villas lights up at dusk.","address":"Akti Koumoundourou 48, 185 33 Piraeus","phone":"+30 210 4175152","hours":"Lunch & dinner daily","maps":"https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1&query=Zefyros+Mikrolimano+Piraeus","verdict":"The one Mikrolimano quay terrace where the history is real: the harbour's oldest fish house, still feeding the classicists.","signature":"Whole day-boat fish, grilled plain: eaten on planks built out over the harbour water","caveat":"Skip it if you want modern cooking or a bargain — this is classic, at view prices.","signal_chip":{"label":"Ath. 2025","full":"Athinorama 2025 — 'the oldest fish house of Mikrolimano, 94 years and counting'","cosign":"and the deck over the water is the real thing"},"dishes":[{"name":"House taramosalata","note":"Whipped pale and light in the kitchen, roe-salted and lemon-sharp, never store-bought.","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Fried kalamarakia","note":"Thin batter over tender rings and sweet tentacles, hot, lemon squeezed at the table.","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Garides Mikrolimano","note":"Prawns baked in tomato with feta melting through, the cove's own dish, bread for the sauce.","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Grilled tsipoura (gilt-head bream)","note":"Skin blistered and salt-crisp over firm white flesh, ladolemono spooned across warm.","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Grilled sole (glossa)","note":"Sweet flat fillets lifting clean off the bone, buttery under oil and lemon.","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Fried shrimp","note":"Shell-on and crisp, eaten whole, tails snapping, salt and a wedge of lemon.","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Grilled karavides (crayfish)","note":"Split and charred over coal, sweet coral-rich tails, warm oil brushed across.","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Horiatiki","note":"Cold tomato, cucumber and onion under a slab of feta and oregano, oil pooling.","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Oysters and raw shellfish","note":"cold, saline, opened to order on the deck","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Seasonal seafood mezedes","note":"clear, classic, no fusion detours","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Greek-vineyard whites","note":"an updated list leaning Greek — ask the season's pick","kind":"drink"}]},
    {"id":"kapileio-tou-zachou","cat":"mainland","tier":"plenty","priority":43,"badge":"Kapileio","name":"To Kapileio tou Zachou","short":"Kapileio tou Zachou","lat":37.9537,"lng":23.66261,"neighborhood":"Piraeus, Kaminia · Komotinis 37, inland","tags":["EUR ~20-30 pp (honest-taverna tier)","Phone ahead at weekends","Weekday lunch among port workers"],"productTags":["Since 2003","Kaminia dive","Barrel wine"],"why":"Kaminia was Piraeus's quarter of brick kilns and stevedores, ten minutes inland from the cruise terminal. In 2003 Christos Zachos and his wife Vagia took over a 1960s grocery-wineshop — a bakaliko-kapileio that already had barrels on the wall and a few tables — and grew a fish kitchen only because the regulars demanded one. Vagia cooks everything; Christos fronts the room, under an Olympiacos shrine and black-and-white harbour photographs. The wine still comes from the kapileio's own barrels. Small fried fish, barrel wine, no ceremony and no sea view — bring cash.","address":"Komotinis 37, 185 41 Piraeus (Kaminia)","phone":"+30 210 4813325","hours":"Midday into evening; Sun lunch peak","maps":"https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1&query=To+Kapileio+tou+Zachou+Kaminia+Piraeus","verdict":"Kaminia's proof that fried small fish, barrel wine and an Olympiacos shrine can outclass the Mikrolimano quay.","signature":"Fried koutsomoura: small red mullet straight from the pan, crisp, sweet, barrel wine beside","caveat":"Not for sea views, card-only wallets, or anyone who needs polish — inland, local, unvarnished.","person":"Vagia — she cooks everything; her husband Christos Zachos fronts the room. In 2003 they took over a 1960s grocery-wineshop that had barrels and a few tables.","signal_chip":{"label":"Ath. '26","full":"Athinorama Jan 2026 — 'fish like the old days, unchanged'","cosign":"and we'd take it over the Mikrolimano quay"},"dishes":[{"name":"Bakaliaros me skordalia","note":"Salt cod fried in a light crust, thick garlic-and-potato purée piled alongside.","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Grilled chtapodi (octopus)","note":"Charred tentacle, tender within, oregano and a splash of vinegar over the top.","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Fried kalamaria","note":"Rings and legs in a thin crust, sweet and hot, lemon at the table.","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Garides Symis (Symi shrimp)","note":"Tiny sweet Symi shrimp fried shell-on, eaten whole with salt and lemon.","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Grilled lavraki (sea bass)","note":"Firm white flesh off the bone, salt-crisp skin, oil and lemon poured over.","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Kolokythoanthoi gemistoi","note":"Zucchini blossoms stuffed with rice and herbs, fried gold, soft and fragrant inside.","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Vrasta horta","note":"Wild greens boiled soft, dressed warm in oil and lemon, faintly bitter.","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Prasotigania","note":"Karditsa leek-and-potato pan-cake, crisp at the edges and soft in the middle.","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Shrimp saganaki","note":"fresh-tomato sauce, feta melting through — Athinorama-praised","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Mussel pilaf","note":"briny rice, dockworker comfort food","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Courgette-and-tomato fritters","note":"taverna-fried, honest, the vegetable course","kind":"dish"},{"name":"Barrel wine","note":"from the kapileio's own barrels — drink what the room drinks","kind":"drink"}]}
